# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: starlink-networking
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:starlink-networking/beamforming] Beamforming can be used for radio or sound waves.
[src:starlink-networking/beamforming] It has found numerous applications in radar, sonar, seismology, wireless communications, radio astronomy, acoustics and biomedicine.
[src:starlink-networking/beamforming] Adaptive beamforming is used to detect and estimate the signal of interest at the output of a sensor array by means of optimal (e.g., least-squares) spatial filtering and interference rejection.
[src:starlink-networking/beamforming] To change the directionality of the array when transmitting, a beamformer controls the phase and relative amplitude of the signal at each transmitter, in order to create a pattern of constructive and destructive interference in the wavefront.
[src:starlink-networking/beamforming] When receiving, information from different sensors is combined in a way where the expected pattern of radiation is preferentially observed.
[src:starlink-networking/beamforming] The beamforming technique involves sending the pulse from each projector at slightly different times (the projector closest to the ship last), so that every pulse hits the ship at exactly the same time, producing the effect of a single strong pulse from a single powerful projector.
[src:starlink-networking/beamforming] The same technique can be carried out in air using loudspeakers, or in radar/radio using antennas.
[src:starlink-networking/beamforming] Receive beamforming can also be used with microphones or radar antennas.
[src:starlink-networking/beamforming] With narrowband systems the time delay is equivalent to a "phase shift", so in this case the array of antennas, each one shifted a slightly different amount, is called a phased array.
[src:starlink-networking/beamforming] A narrow band system, typical of radars, is one where the bandwidth is only a small fraction of the center frequency.
[src:starlink-networking/beamforming] With wideband systems this approximation no longer holds, which is typical in sonars.
[src:starlink-networking/beamforming] In the receive beamformer the signal from each antenna may be amplified by a different "weight." Different weighting patterns (e.g., Dolph–Chebyshev) can be used to achieve the desired sensitivity patterns.
[src:starlink-networking/beamforming] A main lobe is produced together with nulls and sidelobes.
[src:starlink-networking/beamforming] As well as controlling the main lobe width (beamwidth) and the sidelobe levels, the position of a null can be controlled.
[src:starlink-networking/beamforming] This is useful to ignore noise or jammers in one particular direction, while listening for events in other directions.
[src:starlink-networking/beamforming] A similar result can be obtained on transmission.
[src:starlink-networking/beamforming] For the full mathematics on directing beams using amplitude and phase shifts, see the mathematical section in phased array.
[src:starlink-networking/beamforming] Conventional beamformers, such as the Butler matrix, use a fixed set of weightings and time-delays (or phasings) to combine the signals from the sensors in the array, primarily using only information about the location of the sensors in space and the wave directions of interest.
[src:starlink-networking/beamforming] In contrast, adaptive beamforming techniques (e.g., MUSIC, SAMV) generally combine this information with properties of the signals actually received by the array, typically to improve rejection of unwanted signals from other directions.
[src:starlink-networking/beamforming] This process may be carried out in either the time or the frequency domain.
[src:starlink-networking/beamforming] As the name indicates, an adaptive beamformer is able to automatically adapt its response to different situations.
[src:starlink-networking/beamforming] Some criterion has to be set up to allow the adaptation to proceed such as minimizing the total noise output.
[src:starlink-networking/beamforming] Because of the variation of noise with frequency, in wide band systems it may be desirable to carry out the process in the frequency domain.
[src:starlink-networking/beamforming] Beamforming can be computationally intensive.
[src:starlink-networking/beamforming] Sonar phased array has a data rate low enough that it can be processed in real time in software, which is flexible enough to transmit or receive in several directions at once.
[src:starlink-networking/beamforming] In contrast, radar phased array has a data rate so high that it usually requires dedicated hardware processing, which is hard-wired to transmit or receive in only one direction at a time.
[src:starlink-networking/beamforming] However, newer field programmable gate arrays are fast enough to handle radar data in real time, and can be quickly re-programmed like software, blurring the hardware/software distinction.
[src:starlink-networking/beamforming] Sonar beamforming utilizes a similar technique to electromagnetic beamforming, but varies considerably in implementation details.
[src:starlink-networking/beamforming] Sonar applications vary from 1 Hz to as high as 2 MHz, and array elements may be few and large, or number in the hundreds yet very small.
[src:starlink-networking/beamforming] This will shift sonar beamforming design efforts significantly between demands of such system components as the "front end" (transducers, pre-amplifiers and digitizers) and the actual beamformer computational hardware downstream.
[src:starlink-networking/beamforming] High frequency, focused beam, multi-element imaging-search sonars and acoustic cameras often implement fifth-order spatial processing that places strains equivalent to Aegis radar demands on the processors.
[src:starlink-networking/beamforming] Many sonar systems, such as on torpedoes, are made up of arrays of up to 100 elements that must accomplish beam steering over a 100 degree field of view and work in both active and passive modes.
[src:starlink-networking/beamforming] Sonar arrays are used both actively and passively in 1-, 2-, and 3-dimensional arrays.
[src:starlink-networking/beamforming] Sonar differs from radar in that in some applications such as wide-area-search all directions often need to be listened to, and in some applications broadcast to, simultaneously.
[src:starlink-networking/beamforming] In a narrowband sonar receiver, the phases for each beam can be manipulated entirely by signal processing software, as compared to present radar systems that use hardware to 'listen' in a single direction at a time.
[src:starlink-networking/beamforming] Sonar also uses beamforming to compensate for the significant problem of the slower propagation speed of sound as compared to that of electromagnetic radiation.
[src:starlink-networking/beamforming] In side-look-sonars, the speed of the towing system or vehicle carrying the sonar is moving at sufficient speed to move the sonar out of the field of the returning sound "ping".
[src:starlink-networking/beamforming] In addition to focusing algorithms intended to improve reception, many side scan sonars also employ beam steering to look forward and backward to "catch" incoming pulses that would have been missed by a single sidelooking beam.
[src:starlink-networking/beamforming] The delay-and-sum beamforming technique uses multiple microphones to localize sound sources.
[src:starlink-networking/beamforming] One disadvantage of this technique is that adjustments of the position or of the number of microphones changes the performance of the beamformer nonlinearly.
[src:starlink-networking/beamforming] Additionally, due to the number of combinations possible, it is computationally hard to find the best configuration.
[src:starlink-networking/beamforming] One of the techniques to solve this problem is the use of genetic algorithms.
[src:starlink-networking/beamforming] Such algorithm searches for the microphone array configuration that provides the highest signal-to-noise ratio for each steered orientation.
[src:starlink-networking/beamforming] Experiments showed that such algorithm could find the best configuration of a constrained search space comprising ~33 million solutions in a matter of seconds instead of days.
[src:starlink-networking/beamforming] Beamforming techniques used in cellular phone standards have advanced through the generations to make use of more complex systems to achieve higher density cells, with higher throughput.
[src:starlink-networking/beamforming] An increasing number of consumer 802.11ac Wi-Fi devices with MIMO capability can support beamforming to boost data communication rates.
[src:starlink-networking/beamforming] To receive (but not transmit), there is a distinction between analog and digital beamforming.
[src:starlink-networking/beamforming] For example, if there are 100 sensor elements, the "digital beamforming" approach entails that each of the 100 signals passes through an analog-to-digital converter to create 100 digital data streams.
[src:starlink-networking/beamforming] Then these data streams are added up digitally, with appropriate scale-factors or phase-shifts, to get the composite signals.
[src:starlink-networking/beamforming] By contrast, the "analog beamforming" approach entails taking the 100 analog signals, scaling or phase-shifting them using analog methods, summing them, and then usually digitizing the *single* output data stream.
[src:starlink-networking/beamforming] Digital beamforming has the advantage that the digital data streams (100 in this example) can be manipulated and combined in many possible ways in parallel, to get many different output signals in parallel.
[src:starlink-networking/beamforming] The signals from every direction can be measured simultaneously, and the signals can be integrated for a longer time when studying far-off objects and simultaneously integrated for a shorter time to study fast-moving close objects, and so on.
[src:starlink-networking/beamforming] This cannot be done as effectively for analog beamforming, not only because each parallel signal combination requires its own circuitry, but more fundamentally because digital data can be copied perfectly but analog data cannot.
[src:starlink-networking/beamforming] (There is only so much analog power available, and amplification adds noise.) Therefore, if the received analog signal is split up and sent into a large number of different signal combination circuits, it can reduce the signal-to-noise ratio of each.
[src:starlink-networking/beamforming] In MIMO communication systems with large number of antennas, so called massive MIMO systems, the beamforming algorithms executed at the digital baseband can get very complex.
[src:starlink-networking/beamforming] In addition, if all beamforming is done at baseband, each antenna needs its own RF feed.
[src:starlink-networking/beamforming] At high frequencies and with large number of antenna elements, this can be very costly, and increase loss and complexity in the system.
[src:starlink-networking/beamforming] To remedy these issues, hybrid beamforming has been suggested where some of the beamforming is done using analog components and not digital.
[src:starlink-networking/beamforming] There are many possible different functions that can be performed using analog components instead of at the digital baseband.
[src:starlink-networking/beamforming] Beamforming, whether done digitally, or by means of analog architecture, has recently been applied in Integrated Sensing and Communication (ISAC), also known as Joint Communication and Sensing (JCAS), technology.
[src:starlink-networking/beamforming] For instance, a beamformer was suggested, in imperfect channel state information situations to perform communication tasks, while at the same time performing target detection to sense targets in the scene.
[src:starlink-networking/beamforming] Beamforming can be used to try to extract sound sources in a room, such as multiple speakers in the cocktail party problem.
[src:starlink-networking/beamforming] This requires the locations of the speakers to be known in advance, for example by using the time of arrival from the sources to mics in the array, and inferring the locations from the distances.
[src:starlink-networking/beamforming] Compared to carrier-wave telecommunications, natural audio contains a variety of frequencies.
[src:starlink-networking/beamforming] It is advantageous to separate frequency bands prior to beamforming because different frequencies have different optimal beamform filters (and hence can be treated as separate problems, in parallel, and then recombined afterward).
[src:starlink-networking/beamforming] Properly isolating these bands involves specialized non-standard filter banks.
[src:starlink-networking/beamforming] Instead, filters can be designed in which only local frequencies are detected by each channel (while retaining the recombination property to be able to reconstruct the original signal), and these are typically non-orthogonal unlike the FFT basis.
[src:starlink-networking/communications-satellite] A **communications satellite** is an artificial satellite that relays and amplifies radio telecommunication signals via a transponder; it creates a communication channel between a source transmitter and a receiver at different locations on Earth.
[src:starlink-networking/communications-satellite] Communications satellites are used for television, telephone, radio, internet, and military applications.
[src:starlink-networking/communications-satellite] However, most form satellite constellations in low Earth orbit, where ground antennas must track the satellites and switch between them frequently.
[src:starlink-networking/communications-satellite] The radio waves used for telecommunications links travel by line of sight and so are obstructed by the curve of the Earth.
[src:starlink-networking/communications-satellite] The purpose of communications satellites is to relay the signal around the curve of the Earth allowing communication between widely separated geographical points.
[src:starlink-networking/communications-satellite] Communications satellites operate across a wide range of radio and microwave frequencies.
[src:starlink-networking/communications-satellite] To avoid signal interference, international organizations have regulations for which frequency ranges or "bands" certain organizations are allowed to use.
[src:starlink-networking/communications-satellite] This allocation of bands minimizes the risk of signal interference.
[src:starlink-networking/communications-satellite] Clarke published an article titled "Extraterrestrial Relays" in the British magazine *Wireless World*.
[src:starlink-networking/communications-satellite] The article described the fundamentals behind the deployment of artificial satellites in geostationary orbits to relay radio signals.
[src:starlink-networking/communications-satellite] Clarke is often quoted as being the inventor of the concept of the communications satellite, and the term 'Clarke Belt' is employed as a description of the orbit.
[src:starlink-networking/communications-satellite] The first artificial Earth satellite was Sputnik 1, which was put into orbit by the Soviet Union on 4 October 1957.
[src:starlink-networking/communications-satellite] It was developed by Mikhail Tikhonravov and Sergey Korolev, building on work by Konstantin Tsiolkovsky.
[src:starlink-networking/communications-satellite] Sputnik 1 was equipped with an on-board radio transmitter that worked on two frequencies of 20.005 and 40.002 MHz, or 7 and 15 meters wavelength.
[src:starlink-networking/communications-satellite] The satellite was not placed in orbit to send data from one point on Earth to another, but the radio transmitter was meant to study the properties of radio wave distribution throughout the ionosphere.
[src:starlink-networking/communications-satellite] The launch of Sputnik 1 was a major step in the exploration of space and rocket development, and marks the beginning of the Space Age.
[src:starlink-networking/communications-satellite] There are two major classes of communications satellites, *passive* and *active*.
[src:starlink-networking/communications-satellite] Passive satellites only reflect the signal coming from the source, toward the direction of the receiver.
[src:starlink-networking/communications-satellite] With passive satellites, the reflected signal is not amplified at the satellite, and only a small amount of the transmitted energy actually reaches the receiver.
[src:starlink-networking/communications-satellite] Since the satellite is so far above Earth, the radio signal is attenuated due to free-space path loss, so the signal received on Earth is very weak.
[src:starlink-networking/communications-satellite] Active satellites, on the other hand, amplify the received signal before retransmitting it to the receiver on the ground.
[src:starlink-networking/communications-satellite] Passive satellites were the first communications satellites, but are little used now.
[src:starlink-networking/communications-satellite] Work that was begun in the field of electrical intelligence gathering at the United States Naval Research Laboratory in 1951 led to a project named Communication Moon Relay.
[src:starlink-networking/communications-satellite] After achieving the first transoceanic communication between Washington, D.C., and Hawaii on 23 January 1956, this system was publicly inaugurated and put into formal production in January 1960.
[src:starlink-networking/communications-satellite] The first satellite purpose-built to actively relay communications was Project SCORE, led by Advanced Research Projects Agency (ARPA) and launched on 18 December 1958, which used a tape recorder to carry a stored voice message, as well as to receive, store, and retransmit messages.
[src:starlink-networking/communications-satellite] It was used to send a Christmas greeting to the world from U.S.
[src:starlink-networking/communications-satellite] The satellite also executed several realtime transmissions before the non-rechargeable batteries failed on 30 December 1958 after eight hours of actual operation.
[src:starlink-networking/communications-satellite] The direct successor to SCORE was another ARPA-led project called Courier.
[src:starlink-networking/communications-satellite] Courier 1B was launched on 4 October 1960 to explore whether it would be possible to establish a global military communications network by using "delayed repeater" satellites, which receive and store information until commanded to rebroadcast them.
[src:starlink-networking/communications-satellite] After 17 days, a command system failure ended communications from the satellite.
[src:starlink-networking/communications-satellite] NASA's satellite applications program launched the first artificial satellite used for passive relay communications in Echo 1 on 12 August 1960.
[src:starlink-networking/communications-satellite] Echo 1 was an aluminized balloon satellite acting as a passive reflector of microwave signals.
[src:starlink-networking/communications-satellite] Communication signals were bounced off the satellite from one point on Earth to another.
[src:starlink-networking/communications-satellite] This experiment sought to establish the feasibility of worldwide broadcasts of telephone, radio, and television signals.
[src:starlink-networking/communications-satellite] Telstar was the first active, direct relay communications commercial satellite and marked the first transatlantic transmission of television signals.
[src:starlink-networking/communications-satellite] Another passive relay experiment primarily intended for military communications purposes was Project West Ford, which was led by Massachusetts Institute of Technology's Lincoln Laboratory.
[src:starlink-networking/communications-satellite] After an initial failure in 1961, a launch on 9 May 1963 dispersed 350 million copper needle dipoles to create a passive reflecting belt.
[src:starlink-networking/communications-satellite] Even though only about half of the dipoles properly separated from each other, the project was able to successfully experiment and communicate using frequencies in the SHF X band spectrum.
[src:starlink-networking/communications-satellite] An immediate antecedent of the geostationary satellites was the Hughes Aircraft Company's Syncom 2, launched on 26 July 1963.
[src:starlink-networking/communications-satellite] Syncom 2 was the first communications satellite in a geosynchronous orbit.
[src:starlink-networking/communications-satellite] It revolved around the Earth once per day at constant speed, but because it still had north–south motion, special equipment was needed to track it.
[src:starlink-networking/communications-satellite] Its successor, Syncom 3, launched on 19 July 1964, was the first geostationary communications satellite.
[src:starlink-networking/communications-satellite] Syncom 3 obtained a geosynchronous orbit, without a north–south motion, making it appear from the ground as a stationary object in the sky.
[src:starlink-networking/communications-satellite] A direct extension of the passive experiments of Project West Ford was the Lincoln Experimental Satellite program, also conducted by the Lincoln Laboratory on behalf of the United States Department of Defense.
[src:starlink-networking/communications-satellite] The LES-1 active communications satellite was launched on 11 February 1965 to explore the feasibility of active solid-state X band long-range military communications.
[src:starlink-networking/communications-satellite] A total of nine satellites were launched between 1965 and 1976 as part of this series.
[src:starlink-networking/communications-satellite] In the United States, 1962 saw the creation of the Communications Satellite Corporation (COMSAT) private corporation, which was subject to instruction by the US Government on matters of national policy.
[src:starlink-networking/communications-satellite] Over the next two years, international negotiations led to the Intelsat Agreements, which in turn led to the launch of Intelsat 1, also known as Early Bird, on 6 April 1965, and which was the first commercial communications satellite to be placed in geosynchronous orbit.
[src:starlink-networking/communications-satellite] Subsequent Intelsat launches in the 1960s provided multi-destination service and video, audio, and data service to ships at sea (Intelsat 2 in 1966–67), and the completion of a fully global network with Intelsat 3 in 1969–70.
[src:starlink-networking/communications-satellite] When Intelsat was launched, the United States was the only launch source outside of the Soviet Union, who did not participate in the Intelsat agreements.
[src:starlink-networking/communications-satellite] The Soviet Union launched its first communications satellite on 23 April 1965 as part of the Molniya program.
[src:starlink-networking/communications-satellite] This program was also unique at the time for its use of what then became known as the Molniya orbit, which describes a highly elliptical orbit, with two high apogees daily over the northern hemisphere.
[src:starlink-networking/communications-satellite] This orbit provides a long dwell time over Russian territory as well as over Canada at higher latitudes than geostationary orbits over the equator.
[src:starlink-networking/communications-satellite] In the 2020s, the popularity of low Earth orbit satellite internet constellations providing relatively low-cost internet services led to reducing demand for new geostationary orbit communications satellites.
[src:starlink-networking/communications-satellite] Communications satellites usually have one of three primary types of orbit, while other orbital classifications are used to further specify orbital details.
[src:starlink-networking/communications-satellite] MEO and LEO are non-geostationary orbit (NGSO).
[src:starlink-networking/communications-satellite] As satellites in MEO and LEO orbit the Earth faster, they do not remain visible in the sky to a fixed point on Earth continually like a geostationary satellite, but appear to a ground observer to cross the sky and "set" when they go behind the Earth beyond the visible horizon.
[src:starlink-networking/communications-satellite] Therefore, to provide continuous communications capability with these lower orbits requires a larger number of satellites, so that one of these satellites will always be visible in the sky for transmission of communication signals.
[src:starlink-networking/communications-satellite] However, due to their closer distance to the Earth, LEO or MEO satellites can communicate to ground with reduced latency and at lower power than would be required from a geosynchronous orbit.
[src:starlink-networking/communications-satellite] A low Earth orbit (LEO) typically is a circular orbit about 160 to 2,000 kilometres (99 to 1,243 mi) above the Earth's surface and, correspondingly, a period (time to revolve around the Earth) of about 90 minutes.
[src:starlink-networking/communications-satellite] Because of their low altitude, these satellites are only visible from within a radius of roughly 1,000 kilometres (620 mi) from the sub-satellite point.
[src:starlink-networking/communications-satellite] In addition, satellites in low Earth orbit change their position relative to the ground position quickly.
[src:starlink-networking/communications-satellite] So even for local applications, many satellites are needed if the mission requires uninterrupted connectivity.
[src:starlink-networking/communications-satellite] Low-Earth-orbiting satellites are less expensive to launch into orbit than geostationary satellites and, due to proximity to the ground, do not require as high signal strength (signal strength falls off as the square of the distance from the source, so the effect is considerable).
[src:starlink-networking/communications-satellite] Thus there is a trade off between the number of satellites and their cost.
[src:starlink-networking/communications-satellite] In addition, there are important differences in the onboard and ground equipment needed to support the two types of missions.
[src:starlink-networking/communications-satellite] A group of satellites working in concert is known as a satellite constellation.
[src:starlink-networking/communications-satellite] Two such constellations, intended to provide satellite phone and low-speed data services, primarily to remote areas, are the Iridium and Globalstar systems.
[src:starlink-networking/communications-satellite] The Iridium system has 66 satellites, which orbital inclination of 86.4° and inter-satellite links provide service availability over the entire surface of Earth.
[src:starlink-networking/communications-satellite] Starlink is a satellite internet constellation operated by SpaceX, that aims for global satellite Internet access coverage.
[src:starlink-networking/communications-satellite] It is also possible to offer discontinuous coverage using a low-Earth-orbit satellite capable of storing data received while passing over one part of Earth and transmitting it later while passing over another part.
[src:starlink-networking/communications-satellite] This will be the case with the CASCADE system of Canada's CASSIOPE communications satellite.
[src:starlink-networking/communications-satellite] Another system using this store and forward method is Orbcomm.
[src:starlink-networking/communications-satellite] A medium Earth orbit is a satellite in orbit somewhere between 2,000 and 35,786 kilometres (1,243 and 22,236 mi) above the Earth's surface.
[src:starlink-networking/communications-satellite] MEO satellites are similar to LEO satellites in functionality.
[src:starlink-networking/communications-satellite] MEO satellites are visible for much longer periods of time than LEO satellites, usually between 2 and 8 hours.
[src:starlink-networking/communications-satellite] MEO satellites have a larger coverage area than LEO satellites.
[src:starlink-networking/communications-satellite] A MEO satellite's longer duration of visibility and wider footprint means fewer satellites are needed in a MEO network than a LEO network.
[src:starlink-networking/communications-satellite] One disadvantage is that a MEO satellite's distance gives it a longer time delay and weaker signal than a LEO satellite, although these limitations are not as severe as those of a GEO satellite.
[src:starlink-networking/communications-satellite] Like LEOs, these satellites do not maintain a stationary distance from the Earth.
[src:starlink-networking/communications-satellite] This is in contrast to the geostationary orbit, where satellites are always 35,786 kilometres (22,236 mi) from Earth.
[src:starlink-networking/communications-satellite] Typically the orbit of a medium Earth orbit satellite is about 16,000 kilometres (10,000 mi) above Earth.
[src:starlink-networking/communications-satellite] In various patterns, these satellites make the trip around Earth in anywhere from 2 to 8 hours.
[src:starlink-networking/communications-satellite] To an observer on Earth, a satellite in a geostationary orbit appears motionless, in a fixed position in the sky.
[src:starlink-networking/communications-satellite] This is because it revolves around the Earth at Earth's own angular velocity (one revolution per sidereal day, in an equatorial orbit).
[src:starlink-networking/communications-satellite] A geostationary orbit is useful for communications because ground antennas can be aimed at the satellite without their having to track the satellite's motion.
[src:starlink-networking/communications-satellite] In applications that require many ground antennas, such as DirecTV distribution, the savings in ground equipment can more than outweigh the cost and complexity of placing a satellite into orbit.
[src:starlink-networking/communications-satellite] By 2000, Hughes Space and Communications (now Boeing Satellite Development Center) had built nearly 40 percent of the more than one hundred satellites in service worldwide.
[src:starlink-networking/communications-satellite] Geostationary satellites must operate above the equator and therefore appear lower on the horizon as the receiver gets farther from the equator.
[src:starlink-networking/communications-satellite] This will cause problems for extreme northerly latitudes, affecting connectivity and causing multipath interference (caused by signals reflecting off the ground and into the ground antenna).
[src:starlink-networking/communications-satellite] Thus, for areas close to the North (and South) Pole, a geostationary satellite may appear below the horizon.
[src:starlink-networking/communications-satellite] Therefore, Molniya orbit satellites have been launched, mainly in Russia, to alleviate this problem.
[src:starlink-networking/communications-satellite] Molniya orbits can be an appealing alternative in such cases.
[src:starlink-networking/communications-satellite] The Molniya orbit is highly inclined, guaranteeing good elevation over selected positions during the northern portion of the orbit.
[src:starlink-networking/communications-satellite] (Elevation is the extent of the satellite's position above the horizon.
[src:starlink-networking/communications-satellite] The Molniya orbit is designed so that the satellite spends the great majority of its time over the far northern latitudes, during which its ground footprint moves only slightly.
[src:starlink-networking/communications-satellite] Its period is one half day, so that the satellite is available for operation over the targeted region for six to nine hours every second revolution.
[src:starlink-networking/communications-satellite] In this way a constellation of three Molniya satellites (plus in-orbit spares) can provide uninterrupted coverage.
[src:starlink-networking/communications-satellite] The first satellite of the Molniya series was launched on 23 April 1965 and was used for experimental transmission of TV signals from a Moscow uplink station to downlink stations located in Siberia and the Russian Far East, in Norilsk, Khabarovsk, Magadan and Vladivostok.
[src:starlink-networking/communications-satellite] In November 1967 Soviet engineers created a unique system of national TV network of satellite television, called Orbita, that was based on Molniya satellites.
[src:starlink-networking/communications-satellite] In the United States, the National Polar-orbiting Operational Environmental Satellite System (NPOESS) was established in 1994 to consolidate the polar satellite operations of NASA (National Aeronautics and Space Administration) NOAA (National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration).
[src:starlink-networking/communications-satellite] NPOESS manages a number of satellites for various purposes; for example, METSAT for meteorological satellite, EUMETSAT for the European branch of the program, and METOP for meteorological operations.
[src:starlink-networking/communications-satellite] These orbits are Sun synchronous, meaning that they cross the equator at the same local time each day.
[src:starlink-networking/communications-satellite] For example, the satellites in the NPOESS (civilian) orbit will cross the equator, going from south to north, at times 1:30 P.M., 5:30 P.M., and 9:30 P.M.
[src:starlink-networking/communications-satellite] There are plans and initiatives to bring dedicated communications satellite beyond geostationary orbits.
[src:starlink-networking/communications-satellite] NASA proposed LunaNet as a data network aiming to provide a "Lunar Internet" for cis-lunar spacecraft and Installations.
[src:starlink-networking/communications-satellite] The Moonlight Initiative is an equivalent ESA project that is stated to be compatible and providing navigational services for the lunar surface.
[src:starlink-networking/communications-satellite] Both programmes are satellite constellations of several satellites in various orbits around the Moon.
[src:starlink-networking/communications-satellite] Other orbits are also planned to be used.
[src:starlink-networking/communications-satellite] Positions in the Earth-Moon-Libration points are also proposed for communication satellites covering the Moon alike communication satellites in geosynchronous orbit cover the Earth.
[src:starlink-networking/communications-satellite] Also, dedicated communication satellites in orbits around Mars supporting different missions on surface and other orbits are considered, such as the Mars Telecommunications Orbiter.
[src:starlink-networking/communications-satellite] The bandwidth available from a satellite depends upon the number of transponders provided by the satellite.
[src:starlink-networking/communications-satellite] Each service (TV, Voice, Internet, radio) requires a different amount of bandwidth for transmission.
[src:starlink-networking/communications-satellite] This is typically known as link budgeting and a network simulator can be used to arrive at the exact value.
[src:starlink-networking/communications-satellite] Allocating frequencies to satellite services is a complicated process which requires international coordination and planning.
[src:starlink-networking/communications-satellite] This is carried out under the auspices of the International Telecommunication Union (ITU).
[src:starlink-networking/communications-satellite] Within these regions, frequency bands are allocated to various satellite services, although a given service may be allocated different frequency bands in different regions.
[src:starlink-networking/communications-satellite] The first and historically most important application for communication satellites was in intercontinental long distance telephony.
[src:starlink-networking/communications-satellite] The fixed Public Switched Telephone Network relays telephone calls from land line telephones to an Earth station, where they are then transmitted to a geostationary satellite.
[src:starlink-networking/communications-satellite] Improvements in submarine communications cables through the use of fiber-optics caused some decline in the use of satellites for fixed telephony in the late 20th century.
[src:starlink-networking/communications-satellite] Satellite communications are still used in many applications today.
[src:starlink-networking/communications-satellite] Remote islands such as Ascension Island, Saint Helena, Diego Garcia, and Easter Island, where no submarine cables are in service, need satellite telephones.
[src:starlink-networking/communications-satellite] There are also regions of some continents and countries where landline telecommunications are rare to non existent, for example large regions of South America, Africa, Canada, China, Russia, and Australia.
[src:starlink-networking/communications-satellite] Satellite communications also provide connection to the edges of Antarctica and Greenland.
[src:starlink-networking/communications-satellite] Other land use for satellite phones are rigs at sea, a backup for hospitals, military, and recreation.
[src:starlink-networking/communications-satellite] Ships at sea, as well as planes, often use satellite phones.
[src:starlink-networking/communications-satellite] Satellite phone systems can be accomplished by a number of means.
[src:starlink-networking/communications-satellite] On a large scale, often there will be a local telephone system in an isolated area with a link to the telephone system in a main land area.
[src:starlink-networking/communications-satellite] There are also services that will patch a radio signal to a telephone system.
[src:starlink-networking/communications-satellite] In this example, almost any type of satellite can be used.
[src:starlink-networking/communications-satellite] Satellite phones connect directly to a constellation of either geostationary or low-Earth-orbit satellites.
[src:starlink-networking/communications-satellite] Calls are then forwarded to a satellite teleport connected to the Public Switched Telephone Network .
[src:starlink-networking/communications-satellite] As television became the main market, its demand for simultaneous delivery of relatively few signals of large bandwidth to many receivers being a more precise match for the capabilities of geosynchronous comsats.
[src:starlink-networking/communications-satellite] Two satellite types are used for North American television and radio: Direct broadcast satellite (DBS), and Fixed Service Satellite (FSS).
[src:starlink-networking/communications-satellite] The definitions of FSS and DBS satellites outside of North America, especially in Europe, are a bit more ambiguous.
[src:starlink-networking/communications-satellite] Most satellites used for direct-to-home television in Europe have the same high power output as DBS-class satellites in North America, but use the same linear polarization as FSS-class satellites.
[src:starlink-networking/communications-satellite] Examples of these are the Astra, Eutelsat, and Hotbird spacecraft in orbit over the European continent.
[src:starlink-networking/communications-satellite] Because of this, the terms FSS and DBS are more so used throughout the North American continent, and are uncommon in Europe.
[src:starlink-networking/communications-satellite] Fixed Service Satellites use the C band, and the lower portions of the Ku band.
[src:starlink-networking/communications-satellite] FSS satellites are also used to distribute national cable channels to cable television headends.
[src:starlink-networking/communications-satellite] Free-to-air satellite TV channels are also usually distributed on FSS satellites in the Ku band.
[src:starlink-networking/communications-satellite] The Intelsat Americas 5, Galaxy 10R and AMC 3 satellites over North America provide a quite large amount of FTA channels on their Ku band transponders.
[src:starlink-networking/communications-satellite] A direct broadcast satellite is a communications satellite that transmits to small DBS satellite dishes (usually 18 to 24 inches or 45 to 60 cm in diameter).
[src:starlink-networking/communications-satellite] Direct broadcast satellites generally operate in the upper portion of the microwave Ku band.
[src:starlink-networking/communications-satellite] DBS technology is used for DTH-oriented (Direct-To-Home) satellite TV services, such as DirecTV, DISH Network and Orby TV in the United States, Bell Satellite TV and Shaw Direct in Canada, Freesat and Sky in the UK, Ireland, and New Zealand and DSTV in South Africa.
[src:starlink-networking/communications-satellite] Operating at lower frequency and lower power than DBS, FSS satellites require a much larger dish for reception (3 to 8 feet (1 to 2.5 m) in diameter for Ku band, and 12 feet (3.6 m) or larger for C band).
[src:starlink-networking/communications-satellite] They use linear polarization for each of the transponders' RF input and output (as opposed to circular polarization used by DBS satellites), but this is a minor technical difference that users do not notice.
[src:starlink-networking/communications-satellite] FSS satellite technology was also originally used for DTH satellite TV from the late 1970s to the early 1990s in the United States in the form of TVRO (Television Receive Only) receivers and dishes.
[src:starlink-networking/communications-satellite] It was also used in its Ku band form for the now-defunct Primestar satellite TV service.
[src:starlink-networking/communications-satellite] Some satellites have been launched that have transponders in the Ka band, such as DirecTV's SPACEWAY-1 satellite, and Anik F2.
[src:starlink-networking/communications-satellite] NASA and ISRO have also launched experimental satellites carrying Ka band beacons recently.
[src:starlink-networking/communications-satellite] Some manufacturers have also introduced special antennas for mobile reception of DBS television.
[src:starlink-networking/communications-satellite] Using Global Positioning System (GPS) technology as a reference, these antennas automatically re-aim to the satellite no matter where or how the vehicle (on which the antenna is mounted) is situated.
[src:starlink-networking/communications-satellite] These mobile satellite antennas are popular with some recreational vehicle owners.
[src:starlink-networking/communications-satellite] Such mobile DBS antennas are also used by JetBlue Airways for DirecTV (supplied by LiveTV, a subsidiary of JetBlue), which passengers can view on-board on LCD screens mounted in the seats.
[src:starlink-networking/communications-satellite] Satellite radio offers audio broadcast services in some countries, notably the United States.
[src:starlink-networking/communications-satellite] Mobile services allow listeners to roam a continent, listening to the same audio programming anywhere.
[src:starlink-networking/communications-satellite] A satellite radio or subscription radio (SR) is a digital radio signal that is broadcast by a communications satellite, which covers a much wider geographical range than terrestrial radio signals.
[src:starlink-networking/communications-satellite] Amateur radio operators have access to amateur satellites, which have been designed specifically to carry amateur radio traffic.
[src:starlink-networking/communications-satellite] Most such satellites operate as spaceborne repeaters, and are generally accessed by amateurs equipped with UHF or VHF radio equipment and highly directional antennas such as Yagis or dish antennas.
[src:starlink-networking/communications-satellite] Due to launch costs, most current amateur satellites are launched into fairly low Earth orbits, and are designed to deal with only a limited number of brief contacts at any given time.
[src:starlink-networking/communications-satellite] Some satellites also provide data-forwarding services using the X.25 or similar protocols.
[src:starlink-networking/communications-satellite] After the 1990s, satellite communication technology has been used as a means to connect to the Internet via broadband data connections.
[src:starlink-networking/communications-satellite] This can be very useful for users who are located in remote areas, and cannot access a broadband connection, or require high availability of services.
[src:starlink-networking/communications-satellite] Communications satellites are used for military communications applications, such as Global Command and Control Systems.
[src:starlink-networking/communications-satellite] Examples of military systems that use communication satellites are the MILSTAR, the DSCS, and the FLTSATCOM of the United States, NATO satellites, United Kingdom satellites (for instance Skynet), and satellites of the former Soviet Union.
[src:starlink-networking/communications-satellite] India has launched its first Military Communication satellite GSAT-7, its transponders operate in UHF, F, C and Ku band bands.
[src:starlink-networking/communications-satellite] Typically military satellites operate in the UHF, SHF (also known as X-band) or EHF (also known as Ka band) frequency bands.
[src:starlink-networking/communications-satellite] Near-ground *in situ* environmental monitoring equipment (such as tide gauges, weather stations, weather buoys, and radiosondes), may use satellites for one-way data transmission or two-way telemetry and telecontrol.
[src:starlink-networking/communications-satellite] It may be based on a secondary payload of a weather satellite (as in the case of GOES and METEOSAT and others in the Argos system) or in dedicated satellites (such as SCD).
[src:starlink-networking/communications-satellite] The data rate is typically much lower than in satellite Internet access.
[src:starlink-networking/ground-station] A **ground station**, **Earth station**, or **Earth terminal** is a terrestrial radio station designed for extraplanetary telecommunication with spacecraft (constituting part of the ground segment of the spacecraft system), or reception of radio waves from astronomical radio sources.
[src:starlink-networking/ground-station] Ground stations may be located either on the surface of the Earth, or in its atmosphere.
[src:starlink-networking/ground-station] Earth stations communicate with spacecraft by transmitting and receiving radio waves in the super high frequency (SHF) or extremely high frequency (EHF) bands (e.g. microwaves), or in the optical bands for laser communication (then called Optical Ground Station, OGS).
[src:starlink-networking/ground-station] When a ground station successfully transmits radio waves to a spacecraft (or vice versa), it establishes a telecommunications link.
[src:starlink-networking/ground-station] A principal telecommunications device of the ground station is the parabolic antenna.
[src:starlink-networking/ground-station] Ground stations may have either a fixed or itinerant position.
[src:starlink-networking/ground-station] Article 1 § III of the International Telecommunication Union (ITU) Radio Regulations describes various types of stationary and mobile ground stations, and their interrelationships.
[src:starlink-networking/ground-station] Specialized **satellite Earth stations** or **satellite tracking stations** are used to telecommunicate with satellites — chiefly communications satellites.
[src:starlink-networking/ground-station] Other ground stations communicate with crewed space stations or uncrewed space probes.
[src:starlink-networking/ground-station] A ground station that primarily receives telemetry data, or that follows space missions, or satellites not in geostationary orbit, is called a **ground tracking station**, or **space tracking station**, or simply a **tracking station**.
[src:starlink-networking/ground-station] When a spacecraft or satellite is within a ground station's line of sight, the station is said to have a *view* of the spacecraft (see *pass*).
[src:starlink-networking/ground-station] A spacecraft can communicate with more than one ground station at a time.
[src:starlink-networking/ground-station] A pair of ground stations are said to have a spacecraft in *mutual view* when the stations share simultaneous, unobstructed, line-of-sight contact with the spacecraft.
[src:starlink-networking/ground-station] A *telecommunications port* — or, more commonly, *teleport* — is a satellite ground station that functions as a hub connecting a satellite or geocentric orbital network with a terrestrial telecommunications network, such as the Internet.
[src:starlink-networking/ground-station] Teleports may provide various broadcasting services among other telecommunications functions, such as uploading computer programs or issuing commands over an uplink to a satellite.
[src:starlink-networking/ground-station] In May 1984, the Dallas/Fort Worth Teleport became the first American teleport to commence operation.
[src:starlink-networking/ground-station] In Federal Standard 1037C, the United States General Services Administration defined an *Earth terminal complex* as the assemblage of equipment and facilities necessary to integrate an Earth terminal (ground station) into a telecommunications network.
[src:starlink-networking/ground-station] FS-1037C has since been subsumed by the ATIS Telecom Glossary, which is maintained by the Alliance for Telecommunications Industry Solutions (ATIS), an international, business-oriented, non-governmental organization.
[src:starlink-networking/ground-station] The Telecommunications Industry Association also acknowledges this definition.
[src:starlink-networking/ground-station] The ITU Radiocommunication Sector (ITU-R), a division of the International Telecommunication Union, codifies international standards agreed-upon through multinational discourse.
[src:starlink-networking/ground-station] From 1927 to 1932, the International Consultative Committee for Radio administered standards and regulations now governed by the ITU-R.
[src:starlink-networking/ground-station] In addition to the body of standards defined by the ITU-R, each major satellite operator provides technical requirements and standards that ground stations must meet in order to communicate with the operator's satellites.
[src:starlink-networking/ground-station] For example, Intelsat publishes the Intelsat Earth Station Standards (IESS) which, among other things, classifies ground stations by the capabilities of their parabolic antennas, and pre-approves certain antenna models.
[src:starlink-networking/ground-station] Eutelsat publishes similar standards and requirements, such as the Eutelsat Earth Station Standards (EESS).
[src:starlink-networking/ground-station] The Interagency Operations Advisory Group offers a Service Catalog describing standard services, Spacecraft Emergency Cross Support Standard, and Consultative Committee for Space Data Systems data standards.
[src:starlink-networking/ground-station] The Teleport (originally called a *Telecommunications Satellite Park*) innovation was conceived and developed by Joseph Milano in 1976 as part of a National Research Council study entitled, *Telecommunications for Metropolitan Areas: Near-Term Needs and Opportunities*.
[src:starlink-networking/ground-station] A network of ground stations is a group of stations located to support spacecraft communication, tracking, or both.
[src:starlink-networking/ground-station] A network is established to provide dedicated support to a specific mission, function, program or organization.
[src:starlink-networking/low-earth-orbit] A **low Earth orbit** (**LEO**) is an orbit around Earth with a period of 128 minutes or less (making at least 11.25 orbits per day) and an eccentricity less than 0.25.
[src:starlink-networking/low-earth-orbit] The term *LEO region* is used for the area of space below an altitude of 2,000 km (1,200 mi) (about one-third of Earth's radius).
[src:starlink-networking/low-earth-orbit] Objects in orbits that pass through this zone, even if they have an apogee further out or are sub-orbital, are carefully tracked since they present a collision risk to the many LEO satellites.
[src:starlink-networking/low-earth-orbit] The only human spaceflights to go beyond LEO are the lunar missions of the Apollo program from 1968 to 1972 and the Artemis II lunar flyby in 2026.
[src:starlink-networking/low-earth-orbit] All space stations as of 2026 have operated in geocentric orbits within LEO.
[src:starlink-networking/low-earth-orbit] A wide variety of sources define LEO in terms of altitude.
[src:starlink-networking/low-earth-orbit] The altitude of an object in an elliptic orbit can vary significantly along the orbit.
[src:starlink-networking/low-earth-orbit] Even for circular orbits, the altitude above ground can vary by as much as 30 km (19 mi) (especially for polar orbits) due to the oblateness of Earth's spheroid figure and local topography.
[src:starlink-networking/low-earth-orbit] While definitions based on altitude are inherently ambiguous, most of them fall within the range specified by an orbit period of 128 minutes because, according to Kepler's third law, this corresponds to a semi-major axis of 8,413 km (5,228 mi).
[src:starlink-networking/low-earth-orbit] For circular orbits, this in turn corresponds to an altitude of 2,042 km (1,269 mi) above the mean radius of Earth, which is consistent with some of the upper altitude limits in some LEO definitions.
[src:starlink-networking/low-earth-orbit] The LEO region is defined by some sources as a region in space that LEO orbits occupy.
[src:starlink-networking/low-earth-orbit] Some highly elliptical orbits may pass through the LEO region near their lowest altitude (or perigee) but are not in a LEO orbit because their highest altitude (or apogee) exceeds 2,000 km (1,243 mi).
[src:starlink-networking/low-earth-orbit] Sub-orbital objects can also reach the LEO region but are not in a LEO orbit because they re-enter the atmosphere.
[src:starlink-networking/low-earth-orbit] The distinction between LEO orbits and the LEO region is especially important for analysis of possible collisions between objects which may not themselves be in LEO but could collide with satellites or debris in LEO orbits.
[src:starlink-networking/low-earth-orbit] The mean orbital velocity needed to maintain a stable low Earth orbit is about 7.8 km/s (4.8 mi/s), which translates to 28,000 km/h (17,000 mph).
[src:starlink-networking/low-earth-orbit] However, this depends on the exact altitude of the orbit.
[src:starlink-networking/low-earth-orbit] Calculated for a circular orbit of 200 km (120 mi) the orbital velocity is 7.79 km/s (4.84 mi/s), but for a higher 1,500 km (930 mi) orbit the velocity is reduced to 7.12 km/s (4.42 mi/s).
[src:starlink-networking/low-earth-orbit] The launch vehicle's delta-v needed to achieve low Earth orbit starts around 9.4 km/s (5.8 mi/s).
[src:starlink-networking/low-earth-orbit] The pull of gravity in LEO is only slightly less than on the Earth's surface.
[src:starlink-networking/low-earth-orbit] This is because the distance to LEO from the Earth's surface is much less than the Earth's radius.
[src:starlink-networking/low-earth-orbit] However, an object in orbit is in a permanent free fall around Earth, because in orbit the gravitational force and the centrifugal force balance each other out.
[src:starlink-networking/low-earth-orbit] As a result, spacecraft in orbit continue to stay in orbit, and people inside or outside such craft continuously experience weightlessness.
[src:starlink-networking/low-earth-orbit] Objects in LEO orbit Earth between the denser part of the atmosphere and below the inner Van Allen radiation belt.
[src:starlink-networking/low-earth-orbit] They encounter atmospheric drag from gases in the thermosphere (approximately 80–600 km above the surface) or exosphere (approximately 600 km or 400 mi and higher), depending on orbit height.
[src:starlink-networking/low-earth-orbit] Satellites in orbits involving altitudes below 300 km (190 mi) are subject to quick orbital decay due to atmospheric drag.
[src:starlink-networking/low-earth-orbit] Equatorial low Earth orbits (**ELEO**) are a subset of LEO.
[src:starlink-networking/low-earth-orbit] These orbits, with low orbital inclination, allow rapid revisit times over low-latitude locations on Earth.
[src:starlink-networking/low-earth-orbit] Prograde equatorial LEOs also have lower delta-v launch requirements because they take advantage of the Earth's rotation.
[src:starlink-networking/low-earth-orbit] Other useful LEO orbits, including polar orbits and Sun-synchronous orbits, have higher inclinations to the equator and provide coverage for higher latitudes on Earth.
[src:starlink-networking/low-earth-orbit] Some of the first generation of Starlink satellites used polar orbits which provide coverage everywhere on Earth.
[src:starlink-networking/low-earth-orbit] Later Starlink constellations orbit at a lower inclination and provide more coverage for populated areas.
[src:starlink-networking/low-earth-orbit] Higher orbits include medium Earth orbit (MEO), sometimes called intermediate circular orbit (ICO), and further above, geostationary orbit (GEO).
[src:starlink-networking/low-earth-orbit] Orbits higher than low orbit can lead to early failure of electronic components due to intense radiation and charge accumulation.
[src:starlink-networking/low-earth-orbit] In 2017, "very low Earth orbits" (**VLEO**) began to be seen in regulatory filings.
[src:starlink-networking/low-earth-orbit] These orbits, below about 450 km (280 mi), require the use of novel technologies for orbit raising because they operate in orbits that would ordinarily decay too soon to be economically useful.
[src:starlink-networking/low-earth-orbit] A low Earth orbit requires the lowest amount of energy for satellite placement.
[src:starlink-networking/low-earth-orbit] It provides high bandwidth and low communication latency.
[src:starlink-networking/low-earth-orbit] Satellites and space stations in LEO are more accessible for crew and servicing.
[src:starlink-networking/low-earth-orbit] Since it requires less energy to place a satellite into a LEO, and a satellite there needs less powerful amplifiers for successful transmission, LEO is used for many communication applications, such as the Iridium phone system.
[src:starlink-networking/low-earth-orbit] Some communication satellites use much higher geostationary orbits and move at the same angular velocity as the Earth as to appear stationary above one location on the planet.
[src:starlink-networking/low-earth-orbit] Unlike geosynchronous satellites, satellites in low orbit have a small field of view and can only observe and communicate with a fraction of the Earth at a given time.
[src:starlink-networking/low-earth-orbit] This means that a large network (or constellation) of satellites is required to provide continuous coverage.
[src:starlink-networking/low-earth-orbit] Satellites at lower altitudes of orbit are in the atmosphere and suffer from rapid orbital decay, requiring either periodic re-boosting to maintain stable orbits, or the launching of replacements for those that re-enter the atmosphere.
[src:starlink-networking/low-earth-orbit] The effects of adding such quantities of vaporized metals to Earth's stratosphere are potentially of concern but currently unknown.
[src:starlink-networking/low-earth-orbit] The LEO environment is becoming congested with space debris because of the frequency of object launches.
[src:starlink-networking/low-earth-orbit] This has caused growing concern in recent years, since collisions at orbital velocities can be dangerous or deadly.
[src:starlink-networking/low-earth-orbit] Collisions can produce additional space debris, creating a domino effect known as the Kessler syndrome.
[src:starlink-networking/low-earth-orbit] NASA's Orbital Debris Program tracks over 25,000 objects larger than 10 cm diameter in LEO, while the estimated number between 1 and 10 cm is 500,000, and the number of particles bigger than 1 mm exceeds 100 million.
[src:starlink-networking/low-earth-orbit] The particles travel at speeds up to 7.8 km/s (28,000 km/h; 17,500 mph), so even a small impact can severely damage a spacecraft.
[src:starlink-networking/low-earth-orbit] The lifespan of space debris can vary wildly depending on their respective ballistic coefficient, and most importantly their initial orbit altitude.
[src:starlink-networking/low-earth-orbit] At lower orbit altitudes such as 400 km small spacecraft can decay within 5 years.
[src:starlink-networking/low-earth-orbit] However at altitudes above 500 km some spacecraft will take more than 25 years to deorbit.
[src:starlink-networking/low-earth-orbit] The oldest piece of space debris that can be found in LEO is the Vanguard 1 satellite and its third-stage booster.
[src:starlink-networking/low-earth-orbit] The satellite was launched in 1958 and currently has a perigee of 651 km and an apogee of 4,226 km, placing part of its orbit within the higher region of Low Earth Orbit and extending into medium Earth orbit.
[src:starlink-networking/low-earth-orbit] It is currently expected to remain in orbit for 240 years.
[src:starlink-networking/satellite-constellation] A **satellite constellation** is a group of artificial satellites working together as a system.
[src:starlink-networking/satellite-constellation] Unlike a single satellite, a constellation can provide permanent global or near-global coverage, such that at any time everywhere on Earth at least one satellite is visible.
[src:starlink-networking/satellite-constellation] Satellites are typically placed in sets of complementary orbital planes and connect to globally distributed ground stations.
[src:starlink-networking/satellite-constellation] They may also use inter-satellite communication.
[src:starlink-networking/satellite-constellation] Satellites in medium Earth orbit (MEO) and low Earth orbit (LEO) are often deployed in satellite constellations, because the coverage area provided by a single satellite only covers a small area that moves as the satellite travels at the high angular velocity needed to maintain its orbit.
[src:starlink-networking/satellite-constellation] Many MEO or LEO satellites are needed to maintain continuous coverage over an area.
[src:starlink-networking/satellite-constellation] This contrasts with geostationary satellites, where a single satellite, at a much higher altitude and moving at the same angular velocity as the rotation of the Earth's surface, provides permanent coverage over a large area.
[src:starlink-networking/satellite-constellation] For some applications, in particular digital connectivity, the lower altitude of MEO and LEO satellite constellations provide advantages over a geostationary satellite, with lower path losses (reducing power requirements and costs) and latency.
[src:starlink-networking/satellite-constellation] The propagation delay for a round-trip internet protocol transmission via a geostationary satellite can be over 600 ms, but as low as 125 ms for a MEO satellite or 30 ms for a LEO system.
[src:starlink-networking/satellite-constellation] Designing a satellite constellation (i.e., determining the orbital distribution of its constituents) is a complex problem that typically uses satellite-to-target coverage as the primary figure of merit.
[src:starlink-networking/satellite-constellation] Naturally, the resulting constellation depends on the mission requirements and objectives and can be characterized by its geometry.
[src:starlink-networking/satellite-constellation] That is, either symmetric or asymmetric constellations.
[src:starlink-networking/satellite-constellation] Symmetric constellations are traditionally proposed for applications that require global coverage (e.g., telecommunications).
[src:starlink-networking/satellite-constellation] Notable symmetric constellations proposed in the literature include Walker Delta and Star , and Rosette.
[src:starlink-networking/satellite-constellation] Asymmetric constellations are typically adopted when regional coverage (i.e., the distribution of targets is concentrated around specific locations rather than being globally uniform) is required.
[src:starlink-networking/satellite-constellation] Asymmetric constellations are proposed to address disaster monitoring, orbital debris remediation, and cislunar space domain awareness.
[src:starlink-networking/satellite-constellation] The need for optimization in constellation design arises from the large number of degrees of freedom in the design space.
[src:starlink-networking/satellite-constellation] For example, the payload characteristics, required temporal coverage resolution (e.g., continuous or discontinuous), targets' distribution, and candidate orbits.
[src:starlink-networking/satellite-constellation] There are a large number of constellations that may satisfy a particular mission.
[src:starlink-networking/satellite-constellation] Usually constellations are designed so that the satellites have similar orbits, eccentricity and inclination so that any perturbations affect each satellite in approximately the same way.
[src:starlink-networking/satellite-constellation] In this way, the geometry can be preserved without excessive station-keeping thereby reducing the fuel usage and hence increasing the life of the satellites.
[src:starlink-networking/satellite-constellation] Another consideration is that the phasing of each satellite in an orbital plane maintains sufficient separation to avoid collisions or interference at orbit plane intersections.
[src:starlink-networking/satellite-constellation] A class of circular orbit geometries that has become popular is the Walker Delta Pattern constellation.
[src:starlink-networking/satellite-constellation] This has an associated notation to describe it which was proposed by John Walker.
[src:starlink-networking/satellite-constellation] For example, the Galileo navigation system is a Walker Delta 56°: 24/3/1 constellation.
[src:starlink-networking/satellite-constellation] This means there are 24 satellites in 3 planes inclined at 56 degrees, spanning the 360 degrees around the equator.
[src:starlink-networking/satellite-constellation] The "1" defines the phasing between the planes, and how they are spaced.
[src:starlink-networking/satellite-constellation] The Walker Delta is also known as the Ballard rosette, after A.
[src:starlink-networking/satellite-constellation] Ballard's notation is (t,p,m) where m is a multiple of the fractional offset between planes.
[src:starlink-networking/satellite-constellation] Another popular constellation type is the near-polar Walker Star, which is used by Iridium.
[src:starlink-networking/satellite-constellation] Here, the satellites are in near-polar circular orbits across approximately 180 degrees, travelling north on one side of the Earth, and south on the other.
[src:starlink-networking/satellite-constellation] The active satellites in the full Iridium constellation form a Walker Star of 86.4°: 66/6/2, i.e. the phasing repeats every two planes.
[src:starlink-networking/satellite-constellation] Walker uses similar notation for stars and deltas, which can be confusing.
[src:starlink-networking/satellite-constellation] These sets of circular orbits at constant altitude are sometimes referred to as orbital shells.
[src:starlink-networking/satellite-constellation] In spaceflight, an **orbital shell** is a set of artificial satellites in circular orbits at a certain fixed altitude.
[src:starlink-networking/satellite-constellation] In the design of satellite constellations, an orbital shell usually refers to a collection of circular orbits with the same altitude and, oftentimes, orbital inclination, distributed evenly in celestial longitude (and mean anomaly).
[src:starlink-networking/satellite-constellation] For a sufficiently high inclination and altitude the orbital shell covers the entire orbited body.
[src:starlink-networking/satellite-constellation] In other cases the coverage extends up to a certain maximum latitude.
[src:starlink-networking/satellite-constellation] Several existing satellite constellations typically use a single orbital shell.
[src:starlink-networking/satellite-constellation] New large megaconstellations have been proposed that consist of multiple orbital shells.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] In May 2018, SpaceX estimated the cost of designing, building, and deploying the constellation to be at least US$10 billion.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] By the end of 2025, Starlink had become SpaceX's largest business segment, generating $11.4 billion in revenue and $4.4 billion in operating income.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] In addition to civilian broadband service, Starlink is also used for government and military communications, including notably in the Russo-Ukrainian war.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] Its large satellite constellation has prompted discussion regarding its effects on astronomy and orbital congestion.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] Constellations of low Earth orbit (LEO) satellites were first conceptualized in the mid-1980s as part of the United States Strategic Defense Initiative, culminating in Brilliant Pebbles, where weapons were to be staged in low orbits to intercept ballistic missiles on short notice.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] The potential for low-latency communication was also recognized, and development offshoots in the 1990s led to numerous commercial LEO systems using fewer than 100 satellites, such as Celestri, Iridium, and Globalstar.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] Teledesic proposed a broadband "Internet in the Sky," similar to Starlink, with 840 satellites.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] However, some of those entities, including Iridium and Globalstar, went bankrupt.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] Teledesic voluntarily wound down operations due to financing challenges in the wake of the dot-com bubble burst.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] In 2004, Larry Williams, SpaceX VP of Strategic Relations and former VP of Teledesic, opened the SpaceX Washington DC office.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] That June, SpaceX acquired a 10% stake in Surrey Satellite Technology (SSTL) as part of a "shared strategic vision".
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] SSTL was at that time working to extend the Internet into space.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] However, SpaceX's stake was sold back to EADS Astrium in 2008 after SSTL became more focused on navigation and Earth observation.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] In early 2014, Elon Musk and Greg Wyler worked together planning a constellation of around 700 satellites called WorldVu, which would be over 10 times the size of the then-largest constellation, Iridium.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] However, these discussions broke down in June 2014, and SpaceX instead filed an International Telecommunication Union (ITU) application via the Norwegian Communications Authority under the name STEAM.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] SpaceX confirmed the connection in the 2016 application to license Starlink with the Federal Communications Commission (FCC).
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] SpaceX trademarked the name *Starlink* in the United States for their satellite broadband network; the name was inspired by the 2012 novel *The Fault in Our Stars*.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] Starlink was publicly announced in January 2015 with the opening of the SpaceX satellite development facility in Redmond, Washington.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] During the opening, Musk stated there is still significant unmet demand worldwide for low-cost broadband capabilities, and that Starlink would target bandwidth to carry up to 50% of all backhaul communications traffic, and up to 10% of local Internet traffic, in high-density cities.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] Musk further stated that the positive cash flow from selling satellite internet services would be necessary to fund SpaceX's Mars plans.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] Furthermore, SpaceX has long-term plans to develop and deploy a version of the satellite communication system to serve Mars.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] Starting with 60 engineers, the company operated in 2,800 m2 (30,000 sq ft) of leased space, and by January 2017 had taken on a 2,800 m2 (30,000 sq ft) second facility, also in Redmond.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] In August 2018, SpaceX consolidated all their Seattle-area operations with a move to a larger three-building facility at Redmond Ridge Corporate Center to support satellite manufacturing in addition to research and development.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] In July 2016, SpaceX acquired an additional 740 m2 (8,000 sq ft) creative space in Irvine, California.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] The Irvine office would include signal processing, radio-frequency integrated circuit (RFIC), and application-specific integrated circuit (ASIC) development for the satellite program.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] By October 2016, the satellite division was focusing on the significant business challenge of achieving a sufficiently low-cost design for the user equipment.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] SpaceX President Gwynne Shotwell said at the time that the project remained in the "design phase as the company seeks to tackle issues related to user-terminal cost".
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] In November 2016, SpaceX applied to the FCC for a license to operate a "non-geostationary orbit (NGSO) satellite system in the fixed-satellite service using the Ku- and Ka- frequency bands".
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] In September 2017, the FCC granted a license that required half of the constellation to be in orbit within six years and that the full system would be operating within nine years from the date of the license.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] In March 2018, the FCC granted SpaceX approval for the initial 4,425 satellites, with some conditions.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] SpaceX would need to obtain a separate approval from the United Nation's International Telecommunication Union (ITU).
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] The FCC supported a NASA request to ask SpaceX to achieve an even higher level of de-orbiting reliability than the standard that NASA had previously used for itself: reliably de-orbiting 90% of the satellites after their missions are complete.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] In January 2017, SpaceX expected annual revenue from Starlink to reach $12 billion by 2022 and exceed $30 billion by 2025.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] In May 2018, SpaceX expected the total cost of development and buildout of the constellation to approach $10 billion (equivalent to $12,300,000,000 in 2024).
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] In mid-2018, SpaceX reorganized the satellite development division in Redmond and terminated several members of senior management.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] After launching two test satellites in February 2018, the first batch of 60 operational Starlink satellites was launched on May 24, 2019.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] SpaceX said they would meet the deadline of having half the constellation "in orbit within six years of authorization... and the full system in nine years".
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] By July 2020, Starlink's limited beta internet service was opened to invitees from the public.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] Invitees had to sign non-disclosure agreements, and were only charged $2 per month to test out billing services.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] In October 2020 a wider public beta was launched, where beta testers were charged the full monthly cost and could speak freely about their experience.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] Starlink beta testers reported speeds over 150 Mbit/s, above the range announced for the public beta test.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] Pre-orders were first opened to the public in the United States and Canada in early 2021.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] SpaceX later appealed the decision saying they met or surpassed all RDOF deployment requirements that existed during bidding and that the FCC created "new standards that no bidder could meet today".
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] In December 2023, the FCC formally denied SpaceX's appeal since "Starlink had not shown that it was reasonably capable of fulfilling RDOF's requirements to deploy a network of the scope, scale, and size" required to win the subsidy.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] The FCC approved the application in June 2022.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] In 2022, SpaceX announced the Starlink Business service tier, a higher-performance version of the service.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] It provides a larger high-performance antenna and listed speeds of between 150 and 500 Mbit/s with a cost of $2500 for the antenna and a $500 monthly service fee.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] The service includes 24/7, prioritized support.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] Deliveries were advertised to begin in the second quarter of 2022.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] Starlink terminal production was delayed by the 2020–2023 global chip shortage, and only signed up 5,000 subscribers for the last two months of 2021.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] Revenues from Starlink in 2022 were reportedly $1.4 billion, accompanied by a net loss.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] The Starlink business unit had a single cash-flow-positive quarter during 2022.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] On December 1, 2022, the FCC issued an approval for SpaceX to launch the initial 7500 satellites for its second-generation (Gen2) constellation, in three low-Earth-orbit orbital shells, at 525, 530, and 535 km (326, 329 and 332 miles) altitude.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] Overall, SpaceX had requested approval for as many as 29,988 Gen2 satellites, with approximately 10,000 in the 525–535 km (326–332 mi) altitude shells, plus approximately 20,000 in 340–360 km (210–220 mi) shells and nearly 500 in the 604–614 km (375–382 mi) shells.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] The FCC noted that this was not a net increase in approved on-orbit satellites for SpaceX, since SpaceX was no longer planning to deploy 7518 V-band satellites at 340 km (210 mi) altitude that had previously been authorized.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] In March 2023, the company reported that they were manufacturing six Starlink "v2 mini" satellites per day as well as thousands of user terminals.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] The v2 mini had Gen2 Starlink satellite features while being assembled in a smaller form factor than the larger Gen2 satellites.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] The Gen2 satellites required the 9 meters (30 feet) diameter Starship in order to launch them.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] Starlink posted a $30.7 million loss in 2023, and its first year of profitability was 2024, with a net profit of $72.7 million.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] In November 2024, SpaceX proposed a constellation of Starlink satellites around Mars, referred to as "Marslink".
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] The proposed system would be capable of providing more than 4 Mbit/s of bandwidth between Earth and Mars, as well as imaging services.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] In March 2025, the director of the United States Department of Commerce's rural broadband program resigned, citing undue emphasis on Starlink from the Trump administration.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] Also in March, the Department of Government Efficiency (DOGE) installed a Starlink user terminal at the White House complex which raised conflict of interest concerns.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] In response the White House said that the terminal was donated by Starlink and approved by legal counsel and the United States Secret Service.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] Tensions between Brazil and Elon Musk's business ventures escalated in 2024 as the country's telecom regulator Anatel threatened to sanction Starlink after Brazil's top court upheld a ban on X, Musk's social media platform.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] Brazil's President Lula supported the decision, citing X's role in allegedly spreading hate and misinformation undermining Brazil's democracy.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] Brazilian judge Alexandre de Moraes froze Starlink's accounts, and Starlink refused to comply with a court order to block domestic access to X until the freeze was lifted, risking its license to operate.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] In 2024, SpaceX asked its numerous Taiwanese suppliers to move production abroad, citing geopolitical risk concerns.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] This move was questioned by the Taiwanese government and resulted in significant anger from the Taiwanese public, with some pointing out that Starlink was unavailable in Taiwan despite its suppliers providing the underlying technology, and others calling for a boycott of Tesla products.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] Starting in July 2024, SpaceX began conducting tests on Starlink in cooperation with the Romanian Ministry of National Defense and National Authority for Communications Administration and Regulation (ANCOM).
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] These tests aim at demonstrating that the Equivalent Power Flux Density (EPFD) limit can be safely increased, thus improving the speed and coverage area of Starlink, without affecting classic, geostationary satellites.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] The results of these tests will be used to help change a rule set by the International Telecommunication Union in the 1990s regarding the limits of non-geostationary satellites.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] In February 2025, Starlink was part of an investigation by USAID into the agency's oversight of Starlink terminals provided to the Ukrainian government, when USAID's Inspector General was fired by President Trump and all employees put on administrative leave.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] The USAID website was scrubbed of all information related to the Starlink probe.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] In March 2025, Musk's involvement in politics was protested by a number of Starlink customers in the U.K.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] In May 2025, after the Trump administration launched a series of tariffs, the State Department pushed countries to approve American satellite companies, including Starlink.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] Several countries such as India granted regulatory approval to Starlink, hoping that supporting a company owned by Musk would help negotiations to avoid tariffs.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] Starlink provides satellite-based internet connectivity to underserved and remote areas, while also competing with terrestrial broadband providers in urban and suburban markets.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] Starlink also offers mobile connectivity services for uses such as recreational vehicles, maritime vessels, and aviation.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] Terminals for these markets maintain connectivity while in motion.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] Service speeds and latency vary based on network load, location, and service plan.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] Typical latency is lower than that of traditional geostationary satellite internet systems because Starlink's satellites operate in low Earth orbit.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] Independent testing has shown that performance has varied over time as subscriber growth, satellite deployment, and network upgrades have altered available network capacity.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] Because satellite capacity is shared among users within a geographic area, Starlink has implemented network-management policies in some markets.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] These have included waitlists in high-demand regions, deprioritized service tiers, and data-priority systems intended to manage congestion during periods of heavy network utilization.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] Pricing varies by country, service tier, and intended use.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] SpaceX has periodically adjusted prices in response to regional demand and network capacity, including reducing prices in markets where available capacity exceeded demand.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] A Starlink subscriber is counted as one active service line.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] A service line is one internet subscription—usually linked to a specific terminal—and billed under Starlink's standard personal and standard business plans.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] One service line counts as one subscriber, even if multiple people use it.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] Likewise, one person or business can have multiple service lines, which are counted separately.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] It does not include large enterprise or government contracts.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] Prior to SpaceX's initial public offering, Starlink used the words "customers", "subscribers", and "people" without providing the definitions.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] The direct-to-cell service uses Starlink satellites equipped to connect with standard mobile phones without specialized satellite equipment built-in.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] Performance varies depending on network load, location, and spectrum availability, with limited capacity compared to terrestrial mobile networks.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] T-Mobile US and SpaceX launched the first commercial implementation in the United States, using T-Mobile midband PCS spectrum to provide coverage in areas without terrestrial mobile service.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] Initial service supports SMS text messaging, with planned expansion to voice and limited data.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] The system is designed to work with existing LTE-compatible devices.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] On January 8, 2024, SpaceX reported successful SMS testing of the system on T-Mobile's network.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] In April 2023, Rogers Communications announced an agreement with SpaceX to explore satellite-to-phone services in Canada.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] One NZ announced a partnership in the same month to extend mobile coverage across New Zealand, with SMS service expected in 2024 and voice and data in 2025.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] In July 2023, Optus announced a similar partnership in Australia.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] On August 12, 2025, Ukrainian operator Kyivstar conducted a test of the service, with a commercial launch planned for 2025.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] In December 2022, SpaceX announced Starshield, a separate Starlink-based service designed for government and military customers.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] The system is intended for use by the U.S.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] Department of Defense and allied agencies, with options for ownership or leasing of satellites.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] Starshield satellites are described as supporting encrypted communications and resistance to signal jamming, and as capable of hosting a range of payloads.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] Starshield satellites are designed to interconnect with Starlink satellites via optical inter-satellite links.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] Space Force awarded the first Starshield-related contract under its Proliferated Low Earth Orbit program for satellite communications.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] The contract is part of a broader procurement effort involving multiple vendors for military LEO services.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] SpaceX also designs, builds, and launches customized military satellites based on variants of the Starlink satellite bus, with the largest publicly known customer being the Space Development Agency (SDA).
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] SDA accelerates development of missile defense capabilities, primarily via observation platforms, using industry-procured low-cost low Earth orbit satellite platforms.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] In October 2020, SDA awarded SpaceX an initial $150 million dual-use contract to develop 4 satellites to detect and track ballistic and hypersonic missiles.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] The first batch of satellites were originally scheduled to launch September 2022 to form part of the Tracking Layer Tranche 0 of the U.S.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] Space Force's National Defense Space Architecture (NDSA), a network of satellites performing various roles including missile tracking.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] The launch schedule slipped multiple times but eventually launched in April 2023.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] In 2020, SpaceX hired retired four-star general Terrence J.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] O'Shaughnessy who, according to some sources, is associated with Starlink's military satellite development, and according to one source, is listed as a "chief operating officer" at SpaceX.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] While still on active duty, O'Shaughnessy advocated before the United States Senate Committee on Armed Services for a layered capability with lethal follow-on that incorporates machine learning and artificial intelligence to gather and act upon sensor data quickly.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] SpaceX was not awarded a contract for the larger Tranche 1, with awards going to York Space Systems, Lockheed Martin Space, and Northrop Grumman Space Systems.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] In 2019, tests by the United States Air Force Research Laboratory (AFRL) demonstrated a 610 Mbit/s data link through Starlink to a Beechcraft C-12 Huron aircraft in flight.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] Additionally, in late 2019, the United States Air Force successfully tested a connection with Starlink on an AC-130 Gunship.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] In 2020, the Air Force used Starlink in support of its Advanced Battlefield management system during a live-fire exercise.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] They demonstrated Starlink connected to a "variety of air and terrestrial assets" including the Boeing KC-135 Stratotanker.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] Expert on battlefield communications Thomas Wellington has argued that Starlink signals, because they use narrow focused beams, are less vulnerable to interference and jamming by the enemy in wartime than satellites flying in higher orbits.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] In May 2022, Chinese military researchers published an article in a peer-reviewed journal describing a strategy for destroying the Starlink constellation if they threaten national security.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] The researchers specifically highlight concerns with reported Starlink military capabilities.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] Musk has declared Starlink is meant for peaceful use and has suggested Starlink could enforce peace by taking strategic initiative.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] Russian officials including the head of Russia's space agency Dmitry Rogozin, have warned Elon Musk and criticized Starlink, including warning that Starlink could become a legitimate military target in the future.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] Starlink was activated during the Russian invasion of Ukraine, after a request from the Ukrainian government.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] Ukraine's military and government rapidly became dependent on Starlink to maintain Internet access.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] Starlink is used by Ukraine for communication, such as keeping in touch with the outside world and keeping the energy infrastructure working.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] The service is also notably used for warfare.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] Starlink is used for connecting combat drones, naval drones, artillery fire coordination systems and attacks on Russian positions.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] SpaceX has expressed reservations about the offensive use of Starlink by Ukraine beyond military communications and restricted Starlink communication technology for military use on weapon systems, but has kept most of the service online.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] Its use in attacking Russian targets has been criticized by the Kremlin.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] Musk has warned that the service was costing $20 million per month, and a Ukrainian official estimated SpaceX's contributions as over $100 million.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] In June 2023, the United States Department of Defense signed a contract with SpaceX to finance Starlink use in Ukraine.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] In October 2023 after the Gaza war started, users shared the hashtag *#starlinkforgaza* on Elon Musk's social network X (formerly Twitter), demanding he activate Starlink in Gaza after Internet service in the region was lost.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] Musk answered that Starlink connectivity would be provided for aid groups in Gaza.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] At the end of November, Musk said the Starlink service would only be provided for Gaza with the approval of the government of Israel.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] According to the Global Initiative Against Transnational Organized Crime, jihadist groups such as the Jama'at Nasr al-Islam wal-Muslimin and Islamic State – West Africa Province have been using an illicit supply chain to acquire Starlink devices and bypass regulations on their use.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] The more secure communication of these devices has made it harder for government forces to intercept the plans of armed groups, allowing them to evade law enforcement and sustain illicit economies.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] In response, the governments of Niger and Chad have moved to legalize Starlink in hopes of better regulating the technology by requiring registration of the devices.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] However, these measures are unlikely to stop the supply chain.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] Starlink has also been adopted by the Azawadi separatist group, Azawad Liberation Front (FLA), as well as the armed forces of Mali.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] According to an FLA leader in the Tinzaouaten area, the group uses Starlink to coordinate operations, share intelligence, and communicate its narrative.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] In the Battle of Tinzaouaten (2024), the use of Starlink allowed the FLA to maintain secure communication across its dispersed units and release updates on social media, increasing its visibility to external audiences.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] During the 2026 Iran conflict, tensions emerged between the United States Department of Defense and SpaceX over the pricing of Starlink services used for military drone operations.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] Discussions also expanded to the potential use of Starlink Direct-to-Cell services in Iran during internet shutdowns affecting civilian communications.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] The Telegraph later reported that Elon Musk accused the Pentagon of violating Starlink's civilian-use agreements by using the network to support armed drone operations during the conflict.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] The Associated Press reported in 2023 that Brazilian organized criminal groups were making heavy use of Starlink in exploiting remote regions of the Amazon rainforest.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] SpaceX announced in October 2025, that access to at least 2,500 Starlink devices used in Myanmar scamming centers was cut off.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] In Iran, Elon Musk personally announced the activation of Starlink in 2022 after the Iranian government blocked the internet to suppress the spread of anti-government protests, enabling citizens to regain uncensored access.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] These cases illustrate the difficulty governments face in controlling unauthorized satellite communications within their borders.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] The decentralized and autonomous nature of Starlink's operations presents a growing challenge to national sovereignty and cybersecurity enforcement.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] Likewise during the internet blackout amidst the 2025–2026 Iranian protests, Starlink was activated in Iran.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] However, by January 11, the Iranian government reportedly shut down Starlink internet connectivity for the first time.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] The jamming and shut down led to varying degrees of success, with users occasionally being able to circumvent the censorship amidst the security forces also seizing satellite dishes to block any external access.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] The State Department had given SpaceX sanctions exemption to enable Starlink services in Iran, and NGOs including Holistic Resilience and ASL19 had assisted in smuggling terminals into Iran.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] The *New York Times* reported that the Iranian authorities had used GPS spoofing, causing many of the estimated 50,000 Starlink terminals to not operate.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] Several airlines have retrofitted or announced plans to retrofit aircraft with Starlink terminals to provide in-flight internet access.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] Airlines have cited its high bandwidth, low latency, and ability to provide connectivity throughout a flight as advantages over previous systems.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] On April 25, 2022, Hawaiian Airlines announced an agreement with Starlink to provide internet service on its aircraft, becoming the first airline to adopt the system.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] In September 2024, United Airlines announced plans to equip its entire mainline and regional fleet with Starlink connectivity.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] The Federal Aviation Administration approved installation of Starlink equipment on United aircraft in March 2025.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] Qatar Airways began installing Starlink terminals in October 2024.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] In November 2025, International Airlines Group (IAG) announced it would install Starlink terminals on around 500 aircraft of their fleet (Aer Lingus, British Airways, Iberia, Level and Vueling).
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] British Airways was the first IAG airline to fly with Starlink installed in March 2026.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] Also in November 2025, Emirates followed, announcing installations on all 230 aircraft of their active fleet.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] In December 2025, Hanjin Group announced a deal to install Starlink terminals on all aircraft of their fleet, consisting of Korean Air, Asiana Airlines, Air Busan, Air Seoul and Jin Air.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] In January 2026, Lufthansa Group announced Starlink would be installed on all around 850 aircraft of their fleet (including Lufthansa, Austrian Airlines, Brussels Airlines, ITA Airways, Swiss International Air Lines, Air Dolomiti, Edelweiss Air, Eurowings, and Discover Airlines).
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] Singapore Airlines and American Airlines in May 2026, and Wizz Air and El Al in June 2026.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] Within the shipping industry, Starlink is recognized as a 'basic welfare for crew members', allowing location-independent access to telecommunications for sailors.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] Cargo ship lines that have installed Starlink internet on their vessels include Maersk, Hapag-Lloyd, Hyundai Glovis, Korea Line, and others.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] In August 2022, SpaceX secured its first contract for services in the passenger shipping industry.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] Royal Caribbean Group added Starlink internet to its *Freedom of the Seas* liner, and planned to offer the service on 50 ships under its Royal Caribbean International, Celebrity Cruises, and Silversea Cruises brands by March 2023.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] Carnival Corporation & plc added Starlink in 2024.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] Norwegian Cruise Line Holdings added the service in 2023. and MSC Cruises added it in 2024.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] In order to offer satellite services in any nation-state, International Telecommunication Union (ITU) regulations and long-standing international treaties require that landing rights be granted by each country jurisdiction, and within a country, by the national communications regulators.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] As a result, though the Starlink network has near-global reach, including the polar caps, broadband services can be provided in 115 countries as of July 2025.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] SpaceX can also have business operation and economic considerations that may make a difference in which countries Starlink service is offered, in which order, and how soon.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] For example, SpaceX formally requested authorization for Canada only in June 2020, the Canadian regulatory authority approved it in November 2020, and SpaceX rolled out service two months later, in January 2021.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] As of September 2022, Starlink services were on offer in 40 countries, with applications pending regulatory approval in many more.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] Canada was the first outside country to approve the service with Innovation, Science and Economic Development Canada announcing regulatory approval for the Starlink low Earth orbit satellite constellation on November 6, 2020.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] In May 2022, Starlink entered the Philippine market, the company's first deployment in Asia, because of a landmark legislative change (RA 11659, Public Services Act) about all-foreign allowance of company ownership in regard to utility entities such as Internet and telco companies.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] Starlink got provisional permission from the country's Department of Information and Communication Technologies (DICT), National Telecommunications Commission (NTC), and Department of Trade and Industry (DTI) and soon began commercial services, aimed at regions with lower Internet connectivity.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] In June 2023, a license to offer Internet services in Zambia was granted to Starlink by the Zambian Government through its Electronic Government Division – SMART Zambia, after the completion of many trial projects throughout the country.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] In October 2023, Starlink officially went live in Zambia.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] In July 2023, the Mongolian government issued two licenses to SpaceX to provide Internet access in the country.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] In July 2023, it was reported by Bloomberg that attempts to sell the service to Taiwan in 2022 fell through when SpaceX insisted on 100% ownership of the Taiwan subsidiary running Starlink in the country.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] This went against Taiwanese law that required that Internet service providers (ISP) are at least 51% controlled by local companies, an impracticality when dealing with a globe-spanning ISP.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] Japan's major mobile provider, KDDI, announced a partnership with SpaceX to begin offering in 2022 expanded connectivity for its rural mobile customers via 1,200 remote mobile towers.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] On April 25, 2022, Hawaiian Airlines announced an agreement with Starlink to provide free Internet access on its aircraft, becoming the first airline to use Starlink.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] By July 2022, Starlink Internet service was available in 36 countries and 41 markets.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] In May 2022, it was announced that regulatory approval had been granted for Nigeria, Mozambique, and the Philippines.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] In the Philippines, commercial availability began on February 22, 2023.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] In September 2022, trials began at McMurdo Station in Antarctica and from December 2022 on field missions.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] Antarctica has no ground stations, so polar-orbiting satellites with optical interlinks are used to connect to ground stations in South America, New Zealand, and Australia.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] In September 2023, the US-based United Against Nuclear Iran started donating subscriptions and terminals to Iranians to allow them to circumvent Iran's Internet blackout.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] In September 2023, it was reported by some Indian news outlets that Starlink would imminently receive its license to operate in India after Starlink was able to meet all regulatory requirements, but that it would still be required to apply for spectrum allocation in order to provide service.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] SpaceX had earlier sold 5000 Starlink preorders in India, and in 2021 had announced that Sanjay Bhargava, who had worked with Musk as part of a team that founded electronic payment firm PayPal, would head the tech billionaire entrepreneur's Starlink satellite broadband venture in India.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] Three months later, Bhargava resigned "for personal reasons" after the Indian government ordered SpaceX to halt selling preorders for Starlink service until SpaceX gained regulatory approval for providing satellite Internet services in the country.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] In April 2024, it was reported in some Indian news outlets that Starlink had received its "in-principle government approval" and that the approval now "lies at the desk of communications minister Ashwini Vaishnaw".
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] In November 2023, Starlink received the licenses to operate in Fiji.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] The service was launched in Fiji in May 2024.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] In April 2024, it was reported that the company would begin trial service in Indonesia in May.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] Starlink received its license to operate in Indonesia in early May.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] In May 2024, Starlink service was made available for pre-order in Sri Lanka, pending regulatory approval from the Telecommunications Regulatory Commission of Sri Lanka (TRCSL).
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] In August 2024, Starlink Lanka (Private) Limited was granted a Telecommunications Service Provider License by TRCSL, allowing it to operate satellite Internet services in the country.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] However, in March 2025, the government placed the rollout on hold due to concerns over the absence of lawful interception provisions in the license, which were required for national security reasons.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] By June 2, 2025, the Deputy Minister of Technology confirmed that all regulatory conditions had been fulfilled, including the integration of oversight mechanisms, clearing the way for the launch.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] Starlink officially launched its services in Sri Lanka on July 2, 2025.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] In April 2025, Starlink licence was approved by National Communication Authority in Somalia.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] In August 2024, Starlink received the licenses to operate in Yemen.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] Starlink services will soon be implemented through the corporation's sales points distributed across most governorates.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] These points will provide a full range of services, including device sales, activation, subscription fee payments, and direct technical support.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] In April 2025, Houthi rebels in Yemen demanded that residents surrender their Starlink devices.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] In September 2024, United Airlines announced it would install Starlink services on the airline's entire fleet, including mainland and regional aircraft, as part of a plan to offer free high-speed Wi-Fi to all passengers.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] In March 2025, the FAA issued final approval for United to begin equipping its aircraft with Starlink antennas.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] On October 22, 2024, Qatar Airways launched the first Starlink-equipped Boeing 777 flight, flying from Doha to London.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] As of November 2024, Morocco is set to give regulatory approval to Starlink by 2025.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] On March 11 and 12, 2025, Indian telecom companies Airtel and Jio have partnered with Starlink to bring satellite Internet to India, aiming to improve connectivity in remote areas.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] However, the service's rollout is dependent on securing necessary government approvals.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] These partnerships promise to expand broadband access, especially in underserved regions.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] Although Starlink was officially unavailable in South Africa, it was found in June 2025 that Starlink has been operating unlawfully in South Africa since 2022.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] It was reported that South Africans have been able to use Starlink's roaming service for nearly two and a half years as a workaround to the lack of official local support.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] In June 2025 Starlink began notifiying its users of its Roam Unlimited and Global Roaming plans in South Africa that their service had been suspended.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] Earlier in March 2025, Musk claimed that "Starlink can't get a license to operate in South Africa simply because I'm not black".
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] Musk's claim, which likely references the provisions of the South African Electronic Communications Act, 2005, which require telecom licensees to allocate at least 30% equity ownership to historically disadvantaged groups, has been disputed by officials within the South African government.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] In February 2026, Starlink received the licences from the Vietnamese Ministry of Science and Technology to operate fixed and mobile satellite networks in Vietnam, through its local unit headquartered in Hanoi.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] It is expected that Starlink will deploy four ground gateway stations and provide satellite Internet access to up to 600,000 user terminals.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] In June 2026, India froze final approvals for Starlink to begin commercial operations, with security agencies under the Ministry of Home Affairs withholding clearance amid concerns linked to the reported use of Starlink satellite internet terminals during the ongoing Iran conflict.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] According to reports, the decision followed allegations that Starlink terminals were used in the Iran–Israel–United States conflict without authorization, raising security concerns in New Delhi over the control of foreign-operated satellite communication systems during wartime conditions.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] The suspension came despite Starlink having previously secured a Unified License and GMPCS authorization in 2025.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] Treasury Department updated rules regarding export of technology to Iran, allowing Starlink to be exported to Iran in support of the Iranian protests against compulsory hijab, which had triggered extensive government censorship.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] Immediately afterwards, Starlink service was activated in Iran.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] In 2023, the Iranian government filed a complaint with the ITU against SpaceX for unauthorized Starlink operation in Iran.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] In October 2023 and March 2024, the ITU ruled in favor of Iran, dismissing a SpaceX assertion that it should not be expected to verify the location of every terminal connecting to its satellites.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] Iran stated that SpaceX was capable of determining their user terminal locations by citing an October 2022 tweet from Musk saying the number of Starlink terminals operating within Iran was "approaching 100".
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] Despite the illegality of Starlink usage in Iran, the number of Starlink users has skyrocketed via sales of the terminals on the black market.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] Iranian officials have acknowledged that 30,000 terminals in the country, providing access to some 100,000 users.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] In a cyber-blockade carried out in response to the protests in early 2026, the Iranian authorities used military-grade jammers that largely disrupted the Starlink signal.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] Starlink operates a satellite manufacturing facility in Redmond, Washington, and user-terminal manufacturing facility in Bastrop, Texas.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] Starlink's satellite development and manufacturing campus occupies more than 314,000 square feet (29,200 m2) across multiple buildings in Redmond, east of Seattle.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] The first facility opened in 2015, and the company subsequently expanded into additional buildings within the Redmond Ridge Corporate Center.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] Starlink opened a user-terminal manufacturing facility in Bastrop, Texas, east of Austin, in December 2023.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] During its first nine months of operation, the one-million-square-foot (93,000 m2) facility produced one million user terminals.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p01] According to company statements cited by *PCMag*, the facility was projected to become the largest printed circuit board manufacturing site in the United States.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p02] The internet communication satellites were expected to be smallsats, 100 to 500 kg (220 to 1,100 lb) in mass, and were intended to be in low Earth orbit (LEO) at an altitude of approximately 1,100 km (680 mi), according to early public releases of information in 2015.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p02] The first significant deployment of 60 satellites was in May 2019, with each satellite weighing 227 kg (500 lb).
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p02] SpaceX decided to place the satellites at a relatively low 550 km (340 mi) due to concerns associated with space debris from failures or low fuel in the space environment, as well as letting them use fewer satellites than were initially needed.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p02] Initial plans forecasted in January 2015 were for the constellation to be made up of approximately 4,000 cross-linked satellites; more than twice as many operational satellites as were in orbit in January 2015.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p02] The satellites employ optical inter-satellite links and phased array beam-forming and digital processing technologies in the Ku and Ka microwave bands (super high frequency [SHF] to extremely high frequency [EHF]), according to documents filed with the U.S.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p02] While specifics of the phased array technologies have been disclosed as part of the frequency application, SpaceX enforced confidentiality regarding details of the optical inter-satellite links.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p02] Early satellites were launched without laser links.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p02] The inter-satellite laser links were successfully tested in late 2020.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p02] The satellites are mass-produced, at a much lower cost per unit of capability than previously existing satellites.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p02] Musk said, "We're going to try and do for satellites what we've done for rockets." "In order to revolutionize space, we have to address both satellites and rockets." "Smaller satellites are crucial to lowering the cost of space-based Internet and communications".
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p02] In February 2015, SpaceX asked the FCC to consider future innovative uses of the Ka-band spectrum before the FCC commits to 5G communications regulations that would create barriers to entry, since SpaceX is a new entrant to the satellite communications market.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p02] Internet traffic via a geostationary satellite has a minimum theoretical round-trip latency of at least 477 milliseconds (ms; between user and ground gateway), but in practice, current satellites have latencies of 600 ms or more.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p02] Starlink satellites are orbiting at 1⁄105 to 1⁄30 of the height of geostationary orbits, and thus offer more practical Earth-to-satellite latencies of around 25 to 35 ms, comparable to existing cable and fiber networks.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p02] The system uses a peer-to-peer protocol claimed to be "simpler than IPv6"; it also incorporates native end-to-end encryption.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p02] Starlink satellites use Hall-effect thrusters with krypton or argon gas as the reaction mass for orbit raising and station keeping.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p02] Krypton Hall thrusters tend to exhibit significantly higher erosion of the flow channel compared to a similar electric propulsion system operated with xenon, but krypton is much more abundant and has a lower market price.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p02] SpaceX claims that its 2nd generation thruster using argon has 2.4× the thrust and 1.5× the specific impulse of the krypton fueled thruster.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p02] The Starlink system has multiple modes of connectivity including direct-to-cell capability as well as broadband satellite internet service.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p02] Direct-to-cell provides connectivity to unmodified cellular phones and is being offered globally in partnership with various national cellular service providers.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p02] Starlink's broadband internet service is accessed via flat user terminals the size of a pizza box, which have phased array antennas and track the satellites.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p02] The terminals can be mounted anywhere, as long as they can see the sky.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p02] This includes fast-moving objects like trains, and airplanes.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p02] Photographs of the customer antennas were first seen on the internet in June 2020, supporting earlier statements by SpaceX CEO Musk that the terminals would look like a "UFO on a stick.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p02] Starlink Terminal has motors to self-adjust optimal angle to view sky".
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p02] The antenna is known internally as "Dishy McFlatface".
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p02] In October 2020, SpaceX launched a paid-for beta service in the U.S. called "Better Than Nothing Beta", charging $499 (equivalent to $594.2 in 2024) for a user terminal, with an expected service of "50 to 150 Mbit/s and latency from 20 to 40 ms over the next several months".
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p02] From January 2021, the paid-for beta service was extended to other continents, starting with the United Kingdom.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p02] A larger, high-performance version of the antenna is available for use with the *Starlink Business* service tier.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p02] In September 2020, SpaceX applied for permission to put terminals on 10 of its ships with the expectation of entering the maritime market in the future.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p02] The main processor uses several other custom chips such as a digital beam former named *Shiraz* and a front-end module named *Pulsarad*.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p02] The main control unit controls an array of digital beamformers.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p02] Each beamformer controls 16 front-end modules.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p02] In addition the terminal has a GPS receiver, motor controllers, synchronous clock generation and power over Ethernet circuits, all manufactured by STMicroelectronics.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p02] In June 2024, a portable user terminal dubbed "Starlink Mini" was announced to be imminently available.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p02] The Mini supports 100 Mbit/s of download speed and will fit in a backpack.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p02] Initial rollout was in Latin America at a $200 price point.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p02] SpaceX has made applications to the FCC for at least 32 ground stations in the United States, and as of July 2020 has approvals for five of them (in five states).
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p02] Until February 2023, Starlink used the Ka-band to connect with ground stations.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p02] With the launch of v2 Mini, frequencies were added in the 71–86 GHz W band (or E band waveguide) range.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p02] A typical ground station has nine 2.86 metres (9.4 feet) antennas in a 400 m2 (4,300 ft2) fenced-in area.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p02] According to their filing, SpaceX's ground stations would also be installed on-site at Google data-centers world-wide.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p02] MicroSat-1a and MicroSat-1b were originally slated to be launched into 625 km (388 mi) circular orbits at approximately 86.4° inclination, and to include panchromatic video imager cameras to film images of Earth and the satellite.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p02] The two satellites, "MicroSat-1a" and "MicroSat-1b" were meant to be launched together as secondary payloads on one of the Iridium NEXT flights, but they were instead used for ground-based tests.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p02] At the time of the June 2015 announcement, SpaceX had stated plans to launch the first two demonstration satellites in 2016, but the target date was subsequently moved out to 2018.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p02] SpaceX began flight testing their satellite technologies in 2018 with the launch of two test satellites.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p02] The two identical satellites were called **MicroSat-2a** and **MicroSat-2b** during development but were renamed **Tintin A** and **Tintin B** upon orbital deployment on February 22, 2018.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p02] The satellites were launched by a Falcon 9 rocket, and they were piggy-back payloads launching with the Paz satellite.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p02] Tintin A and B were inserted into a 514 km (319 mi) orbit.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p02] Per FCC filings, they were intended to raise themselves to a 1,125 km (699 mi) orbit, the operational altitude for Starlink LEO satellites per the earliest regulatory filings, but stayed close to their original orbits.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p02] SpaceX announced in November 2018 that they would like to operate an initial shell of about 1600 satellites in the constellation at about 550 km (340 mi) orbital altitude, at an altitude similar to the orbits Tintin A and B stayed in.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p02] The satellites orbit in a circular low Earth orbit at about 500 km (310 mi) altitude in a high-inclination orbit for a planned six to twelve-month duration.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p02] The satellites communicate with three testing ground stations in Washington State and California for short-term experiments of less than ten minutes duration, roughly daily.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p02] These are satellites buses with two solar arrays derived from Starlink v1.5 and v2.0 for military use and can host classified government or military payloads.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p02] SpaceX was preparing for the production of Starlink v2 satellites by early 2021.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p02] According to Musk, Starlink v2 satellites will be "...an order of magnitude better than Starlink 1" in terms of communications bandwidth.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p02] SpaceX hoped to begin launching Starlink v2 in 2022.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p02] As of May 2022, SpaceX had said publicly that the satellites of second-generation (Gen2) constellation would need to be launched on Starship, as they are too large to fit inside a Falcon 9 fairing.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p02] Starlink v2 is both larger and heavier than Starlink v1 satellites.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p02] In October 2022, SpaceX revealed the configuration of early v2s to be launched on Falcon 9.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p02] In May 2023, SpaceX introduced two more form factors with direct-to-cellular (DtC) capability.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p02] In August 2025, Starlink tested a "mini laser" to allow connectivity for third party satellites and space stations with the Starlink constellation.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p02] The first six F9-3 satellites with direct-to-cellular (DtC) capability were launched on January 2, 2024, in Groups 7–9.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p02] Between February 2018 and May 2024, SpaceX successfully launched over 6,000 Starlink satellites into orbit, including prototypes and satellites that later failed or were de-orbited before entering operational service.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p02] In March 2020, SpaceX reported producing six satellites per day.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p02] The deployment of the first 1,440 satellites was planned in 72 orbital planes of 20 satellites each, with a requested lower minimum elevation angle of beams to improve reception: 25° rather than the 40° of the other two orbital shells.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p02] SpaceX launched the first 60 satellites of the constellation in May 2019 into a 550 km (340 mi) orbit and expected up to six launches in 2019 at that time, with 720 satellites (12 × 60) for continuous coverage in 2020.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p02] Starlink satellites are also planned to launch on Starship, an under-development rocket of SpaceX with a much larger payload capability.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p02] The initial announcement included plans to launch 400 Starlink (version 1.0) satellites at a time.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p02] Current plans now call for Starship to be the only launch vehicle to be used to launch the much larger Starlink version 2.0.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p02] In March 2017, SpaceX filed plans with the FCC to field a second orbital shell of more than 7,500 "V-band satellites in non-geosynchronous orbits to provide communications services" in an electromagnetic spectrum that has not previously been heavily employed for commercial communications services.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p02] Called the "Very-low Earth orbit (VLEO) constellation", it was to have comprised 7,518 satellites that were to orbit at just 340 km (210 mi) altitude, while the smaller, originally planned group of 4,425 satellites would operate in the Ka- and Ku-bands and orbit at 1,200 km (750 mi) altitude.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p02] By 2022, SpaceX had withdrawn plans to field the 7,518-satellite V-band system, superseding it with a more comprehensive design for a second-generation (Gen2) Starlink network.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p02] In November 2018, SpaceX received U.S. regulatory approval to deploy 7,518 V-band broadband satellites, in addition to the 4,425 approved earlier; however, the V-band plans were subsequently withdrawn by 2022.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p02] At the same time, SpaceX also made new regulatory filings with the U.S.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p02] FCC to request the ability to alter its previously granted license in order to operate approximately 1,600 of the 4,425 Ka-/Ku-band satellites approved for operation at 1,150 km (710 mi) in a "new lower shell of the constellation" at only 550 km (340 mi) orbital altitude.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p02] In total, nearly 12,000 satellites were planned to be deployed, with (as of 2019) a possible later extension to 42,000.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p02] In February 2019, a sister company of SpaceX, SpaceX Services Incorporated, filed a request with the FCC to receive a license for the operation of up to a million fixed satellite Earth stations that would communicate with its non-geostationary orbit (NGSO) satellite Starlink system.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p02] On October 15, 2019, the United States FCC submitted filings to the International Telecommunication Union (ITU) on SpaceX's behalf to arrange spectrum for 30,000 additional Starlink satellites to supplement the 12,000 Starlink satellites already approved by the FCC.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p02] That month, Musk publicly tested the Starlink network by using an Internet connection routed through the network to post a first tweet to social media site Twitter.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p02] In January 2026 SpaceX announced plans to lower approximately 4,400 satellites from their current 550 km orbit to 480 km over the course of the year, citing improved space safety and reduced orbital decay time for decommissioned satellites.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p02] The chart below contains all v0.9 and first generation satellites (Tintin A and Tintin B, as test satellites, are not included).
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p02] Early designs had all phase 1 satellites in altitudes of around 1,100–1,300 km (680–810 mi).
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p02] SpaceX initially requested to lower the first 1584 satellites, and in April 2020 requested to lower all other higher satellite orbits to about 550 km (340 mi).
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p02] In April 2020, SpaceX modified the architecture of the Starlink network.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p02] SpaceX submitted an application to the FCC proposing to operate more satellites in lower orbits in the first phase than the FCC previously authorized.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p02] The first phase will still include 1,440 satellites in the first shell orbiting at 550 km (340 mi) in planes inclined 53.0°, with no change to the first shell of the constellation launched largely in 2020.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p02] SpaceX also applied in the United States for use of the E-band in their constellation The FCC approved the application in April 2021.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p02] On January 24, 2021 SpaceX released a new group of 10 Starlink satellites, the first Starlink satellites in polar / SSO orbits.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p02] The launch surpassed ISRO's record of launching the most satellites in one mission (143), taking to 1,025 the cumulative number of satellites deployed for Starlink to that date.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p02] On February 3, 2022, 49 satellites were launched as Starlink Group 4–7.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p02] A G2-rated geomagnetic storm occurred on February 4, caused the atmosphere to warm and density at the low deployment altitudes to increase.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p02] Predictions were that up to 40 of the 49 satellites might be lost due to drag.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p02] After the event, 38 satellites reentered the atmosphere by February 12 while the remaining 11 were able to raise their orbits and avoid loss due to the storm.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p02] In March 2023, SpaceX submitted an application to add V-band payload to the second generation satellites rather than fly phase 2 V-band satellites as originally planned and authorized.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p02] The FCC limited phase 1 to 7,500 satellites across 3 shells.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p02] Due to delays with Starship development, SpaceX modified the v2 Starlink satellites into a less capable but more compact form factor named "v2 mini", thus enabling these satellites to be launched on Falcon 9.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p02] The first set of 21 of these satellites was launched on February 27, 2023.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p02] SpaceX committed to reducing debris by keeping the Starlink tension rods, which hold the v2 mini-satellites together during launch, attached to the Falcon 9 second stage.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p02] These tension rods were discarded into orbit while launching earlier versions of Starlink satellites.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p02] Observations confirm that v2 mini satellites host two solar panels, like the larger v2 satellites.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p02] As of October 2025, SpaceX has conducted multiple tests of the Starlink deployment system on Starship.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p02] Up to 10 Starlink "simulators" were carried as payload on each test flight starting with Flight 7, expected to be deployed on a sub-orbital trajectory, set to reenter over the Indian Ocean.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p02] Flight 7 failed to reach this objective, as did flights 8 and 9.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p02] Successful tests occurred on Flight 10 and Flight 11, with 8 of 8 Starlink simulators deployed each time.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p02] After the successful launch of Starlink 11-4 the second stage spun out of control and reentered earth's atmosphere over eastern Europe with a fireball visible from Berlin and Sweden as several chunks of space debris crashed into Poland near the city of Poznań.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p02] Several smaller chunks were reported in the village of Wiry, and it is possible some landed in Ukraine, although officials there did not investigate.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p02] The planned large number of satellites has been met with criticism from the astronomical community because of concerns over light pollution.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p02] Astronomers claim that their brightness in both optical and radio wavelengths will severely impact scientific observations.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p02] While astronomers can schedule observations to avoid pointing where satellites currently orbit, it is "getting more difficult" as more satellites come online.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p02] The International Astronomical Union (IAU), National Radio Astronomy Observatory (NRAO), and Square Kilometre Array Organization (SKAO) have released official statements expressing concern on the matter.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p02] On November 20, 2019, the four-meter (13') Blanco telescope of the Cerro Tololo Inter-American Observatory (CTIO) recorded strong signal loss and the appearance of 19 white lines on a DECam shot (right image).
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p02] This image noise was correlated to the transit of a Starlink satellite train, launched a week earlier.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p02] SpaceX representatives and Musk have claimed that the satellites will have minimal impact, being easily mitigated by pixel masking and image stacking.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p02] However, professional astronomers have disputed these claims based on initial observation of the Starlink v0.9 satellites on the first launch, shortly after their deployment from the launch vehicle.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p02] In later statements on Twitter, Musk stated that SpaceX will work on reducing the albedo of the satellites and will provide on-demand orientation adjustments for astronomical experiments, if necessary.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p02] One Starlink satellite (Starlink 1130 / DarkSat) launched with an experimental coating to reduce its albedo.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p02] The reduction in g-band magnitude is 0.8 magnitude (55%).
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p02] Despite these measures, astronomers found that the satellites were still too bright, thus making DarkSat essentially a "dead end".
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p02] On April 17, 2020, SpaceX wrote in an FCC filing that it would test new methods of mitigating light pollution, and also provide access to satellite tracking data for astronomers to "better coordinate their observations with our satellites".
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p02] On April 27, 2020, Musk announced that the company would introduce a new sunshade designed to reduce the brightness of Starlink satellites.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p02] As of 15 October 2020, over 200 Starlink satellites had a sunshade.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p02] An October 2020 analysis found them to be only marginally fainter than DarkSat.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p02] A January 2021 study pinned the brightness at 31% of the original design.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p02] According to a May 2021 study, "A large number of fast-moving transmitting stations (i.e. satellites) will cause further interference.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p02] New analysis methods could mitigate some of these effects, but data loss is inevitable, increasing the time needed for each study and limiting the overall amount of science done".
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p02] In February 2022, the International Astronomical Union (IAU) established a center to help astronomers deal with the adverse effects of satellite constellations such as Starlink.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p02] Work will include the development of software tools for astronomers, advancement of national and international policies, community outreach and work with industry on relevant technologies.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p02] In June 2022, the IAU released a website for astronomers to deal with some adverse effects via satellite tracking.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p02] This will enable astronomers to be able to track satellites to be able to avoid and time them for minimal impact on current work.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p02] The first batch of Generation 2 spacecraft was launched in February 2023.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p02] These satellites are referred to as "Mini" because they are smaller than the full-sized Gen 2 spacecraft that will come later.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p02] SpaceX uses brightness mitigation for Gen 2 that includes a mirror-like surface which reflects sunlight back into space and they orient the solar panels so that observers on the ground only see the dark sides.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p02] The Minis are fainter than Gen 1 spacecraft despite being four times as large according to an observational study published in June 2023.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p02] They are 44% as bright as VisorSats, 24% compared to V1.5 and 19% compared to the original design which had no brightness mitigation.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p02] Minis appear 12 times brighter before they reach the target orbit.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p02] The paper concluded that these emissions will be "detrimental to key SKA science goals without future mitigation".
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p02] The large number of satellites employed by Starlink may create the long-term danger of space debris resulting from placing thousands of satellites in orbit and the risk of causing a satellite collision, potentially triggering a cascade phenomenon known as Kessler syndrome.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p02] SpaceX has said that most of the satellites are launched at a lower altitude, and failed satellites are expected to deorbit within five years without propulsion. in near-Earth orbit.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p02] According to SpaceX's semiannual reports filed with the Federal Communications Commission, Starlink satellites performed approximately 50,000 collision-avoidance maneuvers between December 1, 2023, and May 31, 2024, about double the number from the previous six-month period.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p02] This represented an average of 14 maneuvers per satellite during the six-month period.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p02] Early in the program, a near-miss occurred when SpaceX did not move a satellite that had a 1 in 1,000 chance of colliding with a European one, ten times higher than the ESA's threshold for avoidance maneuvers.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p02] SpaceX subsequently fixed an issue with its paging system that had disrupted emails between the ESA and SpaceX.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p02] The ESA said it plans to invest in technologies to automate satellite collision avoidance maneuvers.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p02] In 2021, Chinese authorities lodged a complaint with the United Nations, saying their space station had performed evasive maneuvers that year to avoid Starlink satellites.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p02] In the document, Chinese delegates said that the continuously maneuvering Starlink satellites posed a risk of collision, and two close encounters with the satellites in July and October constituted dangers to the life or health of astronauts aboard the Chinese Tiangong space station.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p02] The destruction of the Russian satellite Kosmos 1408 in November 2021 by an anti-satellite weapon test impacted Starlink operations.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p02] According to SpaceX reports, over 1,700 out of 6,873 collision avoidance maneuvers performed by Starlink satellites between December 1, 2021, and May 31, 2022, were to avoid Kosmos 1408 debris.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p02] SpaceX satellites will maneuver if the probability of collision is greater than 10−6 (1 in 1,000,000 chance of collision), compared to the industry standard of 10−4 (1 in 10,000 chance of collision).
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p02] SpaceX has budgeted sufficient propellant to accommodate approximately 5,000 propulsive maneuvers over the life of a Gen2 satellite, including a budget of approximately 350 collision avoidance maneuvers per satellite over that time period.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p02] As of May 2022, the average Starlink satellite had conducted fewer than three collision-avoidance maneuvers over the 6 preceding months.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p02] Telesat announced a smaller 117 satellite constellation in 2015 with plans to deliver initial service in 2021.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p02] In February 2015, financial analysts questioned established geosynchronous orbit communications satellite fleet operators as to how they intended to respond to the competitive threat of SpaceX and OneWeb LEO communication satellites.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p02] In October 2015, SpaceX President Gwynne Shotwell indicated that while development continues, the business case for the long-term rollout of an operational satellite network was still in an early phase.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p02] By October 2017, the expectation for large increases in satellite network capacity from emerging lower-altitude broadband constellations caused market players to cancel some planned investments in new geosynchronous orbit broadband communications satellites.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p02] SpaceX was challenged regarding Starlink in February 2021 when the National Rural Electric Cooperative Association (NRECA), a political interest group representing traditional rural internet service providers, urged the U.S.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p02] Federal Communications Commission (FCC) to "actively, and aggressively, and thoughtfully vet" the subsidy applications of SpaceX and other broadband providers.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p02] At the time, SpaceX had provisionally won $886 million for a commitment to provide service to approximately 643,000 locations in 35 states as part of the Rural Digital Opportunity Fund (RDOF).
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p02] Additionally, Jim Matheson, chief executive officer of the NRECA voiced concern about technologies that had not yet been proven to meet the high speeds required for the award category.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p02] Starlink was specifically criticized for being still in beta testing and for unproven technology.
[src:starlink-networking/starlink-p02] While Starlink is deployed worldwide, it has encountered trademark conflicts in some countries such as Mexico and Ukraine.
